The information presented in this section will provide you with a greater understanding of topics related to laws and ethics applicable to General Lines of insurance. This chapter is not required for your state exam, but is included as part of your producer prelicensing education.

Any individual or entity that transacts insurance in the state of Florida is required to be licensed; the license type required is based on the lines of insurance transacted.

Upon completion of this chapter, you will:

Have working knowledge about the jurisdiction of duties and responsibilities of Florida’s Chief Financial Officer (CFO), the Department of Financial Services (DFS), the Office of Insurance Regulation (OIR), and the Office of Financial Regulation (OFR);
Be familiar with the licensing requirements of general lines agents, as well as those of insurance agencies, including the grounds for refusal, suspension, or revocation of insurance licenses and appointments;
Understand the duties of licensed and unlicensed personnel in the insurance industry;
Have completed a review of advertising and recordkeeping requirements, the Florida Insurance Guaranty Association (FIGA), and details about Department communication;
Understand and be able to explain updated Florida laws and federal laws as they pertain to Florida licensees;
Be conversant in the DFS’ code of ethics and related rules, marketing regulations and ethical guidelines, industry products and suitability with respect to sales and service, unfair methods of competition and unfair/deceptive acts and practices in Florida, and required premium discounts; and
Have completed a review of new and other important terminology that applies to Florida licensees, unauthorized products and entities involved in Florida commerce, and recent violations and enforcement actions of Florida licensees.

Regulatory Awareness
1. Jurisdiction of Duties and Responsibilities
The insurance industry in the United States is regulated primarily by the states. In the state of Florida, the insurance regulatory bodies include

The Department of Financial Services (DFS);
The Office of Insurance Regulation (OIR); and
The Office of Financial Regulation (OFR).
Department of Financial Services (DFS)
The Department of Financial Services (DFS) was established in 2003 by merging the state’s Departments of Insurance, Treasury, Banking and Finance, and State Fire Marshal. The DFS consists of 14 divisions and several specialized offices for the purpose of carrying out the statutory duties of the state of Florida.

The service divisions of the DFS include

Consumer Services;
Fiscal integrity (formerly Accounting and Auditing);
Funeral, Cemetery, and Consumer Services;
Insurance Agent and Agency Services;
Investigative and Forensic Services (formerly Insurance Fraud);
Public Assistance Fraud;
Rehabilitation and Liquidation;
Risk Management;
Treasury;
State Fire Marshal; and
Workers Compensation.
The DFS is headed by the Chief Financial Officer (CFO), who is also the State Fire Marshal and is a member of the Florida Cabinet. The CFO is responsible for the state’s accounting and auditing functions, monitors the investment of state funds, and manages the risk management and deferred compensation programs for the state. The CFO also handles insurance consumer services, oversees insurance fraud investigations, and is responsible for the licensing and supervision of insurance agents, insurance agencies, funeral homes, and cemeteries.

Financial Services Commission (Commission)
The Financial Services Commission (the Commission) was established to protect the public by regulating the insurance, securities, and banking industries in the state of Florida. The Commission includes the Governor, Attorney General, Chief Financial Officer, and Commissioner of Agriculture and is responsible for appointing the officials who oversee the Office of Insurance Regulation (OIR) and the Office of Financial Regulation (OFR). The OIR and the OFR report directly to the Commission.

Office of Insurance Regulation (OIR)
The Office of Insurance Regulation is responsible for all activities that concern insurance companies and risk-bearing entities, including rate-setting, approval of policy forms, market conduct, claim settlement, issuance of certificates of authority, insurer solvency, viatical settlements, premium financing, and administrative supervision. The Commissioner of Insurance (also referred to as the Director of the Office of Insurance Regulation) heads the OIR.

Office of Financial Regulation (OFR)
The Office of Financial Regulation is responsible for all activities of the Financial Services Commission with respect to the regulation of banks, credit unions, other financial institutions, finance companies, and the securities industry. The Commissioner of Financial Regulation (also referred to as the Director of the Office of Financial Regulation) heads the OFR.

2. Licensing Requirements
Appointment
Insurance agents, adjusters, customer service representatives, agencies, and managing general agents must be both licensed and appointed before acting or advertising as an insurance licensee in Florida. In addition, agents and representatives must be licensed before soliciting insurance, which is defined by statute as attempting to persuade an individual or entity to purchase any type of insurance product by

Describing a policy’s terms, premiums, or rates of return (i.e., explaining a policy or its coverages, cost, or interest-bearing features);
Distributing an invitation to contract (i.e., soliciting insurance);
Completing insurance applications or orders;
Comparing insurance products, offering insurance advice, or interpreting insurance coverages or policies; or
Offering or attempting to negotiate a viatical settlement on behalf of another.
When appointed by an insurer, an individual may only hold appointments for lines of insurance for which he or she is licensed. A separate appointment is required for each insurer for whom an individual is appointed as an agent.

Appointments are only valid for the party to whom they are issued and cannot be transferred to another individual or entity. Licensees are not permitted to authorize other individuals or entities to transact insurance using, or under, their appointments.

Contact Information
Individuals
Each insurance license is required to contain specific information, which is requested on the original application for license. A license application requires the applicant’s full name, age, Social Security number, residence and business addresses, mailing address, contact telephone numbers (one of which must be a business telephone number), and a contact email address.

All licensees are required to notify the Department in writing within 30 days of any change in this information. If a licensee’s residence or principal business address is moved to another state, all appointments and licensees will be terminated by the Department immediately.

A fine of $250 applies to any licensee who fails to notify the Department of a change of address or name within the required time frame. Subsequent offenses will result in a fine of at least $500 or suspension or revocation of the license.

Contact information must be updated on the licensee’s MyProfile account on the OIR website; however, changes or updates to a licensee’s name, date of birth, or Social Security number must be submitted in writing to the DFS Bureau of Agent and Agency Licensing at 200 E. Gaines Street, Room 419, Tallahassee, FL 32399-0319.

Businesses and Trade Names
If an individual transacts business under a name other than his or her given name (i.e., under a trade or business name), the agent must notify the Department within 30 days after first transacting insurance using that business name. The notice must be filed on forms approved by the Department that include the business name or names being used, the addresses of any business offices using the business name, and the name and Social Security number of every corporate officer and director or other individual associated with the firm or corporation.

If the name or address associated with any business name is changed, or if the name or address of the business’ personnel, director, or officer changes, the change must be filed with the Department within 30 days of the change. The same requirement applies if any licensee terminates use of, or association with, the firm to which the business name applies or if information contained in the business’s application to the Department changes.

MyProfile
The Department of Financial Services’ Division of Agent and Agency Services requires agents to create an online account in MyProfile, which is the interface between licensees and the Division.

Individuals can perform the following transactions on MyProfile:

Verify a name;
Verify or change an address;
Apply for a Letter of Certification or a Letter of Clearance;
View information and deficiencies on a pending license application;
View licenses and appointments;
Apply for agent and adjuster licenses;
Check CE status; and
Obtain a duplicate license.
Insurance agencies can perform the following transactions on MyProfile:

Verify a name;
Verify an address;
Apply for an agency license; and
Update agency information.
The MyProfile page on the DFS website contains a login page, an education database, and online guides and tutorials. Once an individual has met all licensing requirements, the Department will email its approval for licensure. The individual may then visit his or her MyProfile account to print the license.

All address and contact information MUST be updated and/or verified through the agent’s MyProfile account. However, name, date of birth, and Social Security number changes must be submitted in writing to the Department, with legible supporting documentation (i.e., marriage certificate, articles of incorporation, Social Security card).
MyProfile contains the Education Database, which provides prelicensing and continuing education information, including state requirements. No login is required to access this online information.

Insurance Agency Licensing
In Florida, an insurance agency can be an individual, firm, partnership, corporation, association, or any type of entity so long as it is not an employee of the entity or an adjuster. An insurance agency engages in any activity that, by state law, can only be conducted by a licensed insurance agent; this includes an individual employee who engages in such activity.

Insurance agencies must possess an insurance agency license for every location at which they transact business for which an insurance license is required. An exemption to this requirement exists for agencies that are owned by a single licensed insurance agent doing business in his or her own personal name and who does not employ or subcontract other licensed agents and/or representatives.

If an insurance agency establishes a branch office, the branch office is considered a branch agency and does not need to secure its own license as long as the agency does all of the following:

Transacts business under the same name and federal tax identification number as the licensed agency;
Designates a licensed agent in charge of the branch office, as required by law, with the Department; and
Submits to the Department a request for the branch agency’s address and telephone number to be included in the licensing record of the licensed agency within 30 days after the branch agency begins transacting insurance.
Insurance agencies failing to submit a request for a license as required by law are subject to imposition of an administrative penalty up to $10,000. Beginning October 1, 2015, all insurance agency registrations will be converted to insurance agency licenses automatically.

Applications for an insurance agency license must be submitted in writing (or via MyProfile) and comply with the following requirements: 

Include the signature of at least one of the following individuals, whose names and residence addresses are required to be listed on the application if they direct or participate in the management or control of the agency in any manner: each owner, partner, officer, director, president, senior vice president, secretary, treasurer, and limited liability company member; and
Include the following agency information:
Name, principal business street address, and valid email address;
Name, address, and email address of the agency’s registered agent or other party authorized to accept service on behalf of the agency;
For each branch agency, the name, physical address, telephone number, email address, and the date the branch agency began transacting insurance;
The name of its full-time agent in charge, including the names of any agents in charge of the agency’s branch offices, and applicable location addresses; and
The fingerprints of any sole proprietor, each individual required to be listed in the application, and each individual who directs or participates in the management or control of an incorporated agency that does not trade its shares on a securities exchange.
Once an insurance agency license is issued, it must be displayed prominently in the agency in a location where it is clearly visible to any visiting clients or potential clients.

If an insurance agency requests licensure in a name other than the natural name of an individual, the Department may refuse to issue a license if the true or fictitious name

Is too similar to the name used by another agency or insurer or interferes with another agency or insurer;
Misleads the public in any fashion; or
States or implies the agency is an insurer, motor club, hospital service plan, state or federal agency, charitable organization, or entity whose primary purpose is to provide advice and counsel rather than sell or solicit insurance.
The agent in charge of each insurance agency and its branch agencies must be the licensed and appointed agent responsible for the supervision of all employees of the agency location, regardless of whether the agent in charge actually transacts insurance or meets with the public. The agent in charge must hold an agent’s license for at least two of the lines of insurance being sold or serviced at that branch location. (If only one line of insurance is being sold or serviced, the agent in charge is only required to be licensed in that line of insurance.) The agent in charge is accountable for misconduct and all violations of Insurance Code that may be committed by any agency employee or individual under his or her supervision while acting on behalf of the agency.

Insurance agencies may NOT transact insurance unless they have designated, and are receiving the services of, an agent in charge. Furthermore, all changes to the designation of the agent in charge of any branch location must be reported to the Department within 30 days.
If an agency’s agent in charge terminates his or her affiliation with the agency for any reason, another agent in charge must be designated within 30 days. Such designation must be reported to the Department within that 30-day period. If the agency fails to designate a replacement for the terminated agent in charge for 90 continuous days, the agency license expires automatically on the 91st day after the agent in charge’s termination of affiliation.

Transfer, Surrender, and Termination of License
Insurance licenses and appointments issued in Florida are only valid with respect to the party to whom they are issued; licenses cannot be transferred to any other individual or entity. In addition, licensees are prohibited from permitting any other person to transact insurance under their license.

Transfer
Agents who are licensed in good standing as a resident in another state may transfer their licenses to Florida for the same lines of authority contained on their resident licenses unless the Department finds grounds for refusal. Eligibility criteria for the transfer include:

The individual must become a resident of Florida;
The individual must have been licensed in the other state for at least one year immediately preceding the date of becoming a Florida resident;
The license application must include all requirements and be submitted within 90 days of the individual establishing residency in Florida; requirements include a set of fingerprints and a letter of certification from the applicant’s home state;
Satisfaction of prelicensing education requirements for Florida, unless the applicant’s home state had equivalent prelicensing education requirements; and
Satisfaction of the examination requirements in Florida.
Surrender
All insurance licenses issued in Florida are considered the property of the state and will be invalid and no longer in effect if refused, suspended, revoked, nonrenewed, expired, or otherwise terminated. Licensees are only required to surrender their physical licenses to the Department at the request of the Department.

Termination
Florida insurance licenses can be terminated for any of several reasons, which include refusal, suspension, or revocation. In addition, insurance licenses and appointments are revoked automatically if the licensee is convicted in court of violating Insurance Code or committing a felony. Once a license is revoked automatically for these reasons, the licensee is entitled to an expedited hearing to determine only if the revocation should be reversed because the license was not actually convicted. If a hearing is held, any documents, reports, or other evidence submitted in relation to the license revocation will remain confidential and exempt from being made public until they have been published at the hearing.

If a Florida insurance license is suspended or revoked, the term of the suspension or revocation cannot be longer than two years. During the term of the suspension or revocation, the licensee:

Will also have all appointments suspended/revoked concurrently with the license;
Will not be eligible, or have the right, to apply for any other insurance license;
Cannot receive a license reinstatement without submitting, and receiving approval of, a reinstatement application; and
In the event of a second license suspension or revocation, be required to complete approved continuing education courses before applying for reinstatement.
The license will remain suspended or revoked, along with all appointments and eligibility for licensure, unless the suspension/revocation is rescinded or modified by the Department.

Once an individual’s agent or customer representative license, or eligibility for licensure, has been revoked on two separate occasions, that individual is prohibited from ever being issued any type of Florida insurance license in the future. Similarly, if such an individual has his or her insurance license revoked for any offense related to the sales or solicitation of insurance to a person age 65 or older, the individual can no longer be issued an insurance license in Florida, nor will he or she ever become eligible for an insurance license in Florida. 

During the term of an insurance license’s suspension or revocation, the licensee is not permitted to engage in any activity for which an insurance license or appointment is required. This prohibition includes attempting, or claiming, to engage in such an activity or being employed in any manner by an insurance agent, adjuster, insurance agency, or insurance adjusting firm.

When the term of a suspension or revocation has expired, a new or reinstated license cannot be issued to the licensee if any of the circumstances for which the license was terminated still exist. When requesting the issuance of a new or reinstated license after a suspension or revocation, the licensee is required to submit an application under the same requirements that apply for a first-time applicant for licensure.

If a single license, or eligibility for a license, is suspended or revoked, all other insurance licenses and appointments for that licensee will also be suspended or revoked. If a general lines agent’s license or eligibility for licensure is suspended or revoked, the licenses of any agents who are employed by, or members of, the agent will also be suspended or revoked if they knowingly participated in any act that formed the basis of the suspension or revocation of the general lines agent’s license. If an insurance agency’s license is suspended or revoked, the license of any licensee under the management, ownership, control, or directorship of any licensee that participated in activities that caused the original agency’s license suspension/revocation) may also be suspended or revoked.

Grounds for Refusal, Suspension, or Revocation of Insurance Licenses and Appointments
Insurance licensees are required to behave in a professional, ethical, legal fashion at all times, and especially when transacting insurance. Failure to comply with laws and/or the state’s code of ethics may result in a licensee, or a license applicant, experiencing a license refusal, suspension, or revocation.

Certain conduct results in automatic, or compulsory, license termination or loss of eligibility for licensure and appointment. Other conduct constitutes grounds for discretionary termination. The standards for licensure of agents, customer representatives, adjusters, service representatives, managing general agents are the same; however, other standards apply to insurance agencies.

Grounds for Compulsory License Refusal, Suspension, or Revocation
Applicants, Agents, Customer Representatives, Service Representatives, MGAs
If the following conditions exist, the license and appointment of an applicant, agent, customer representative, service representative, or managing general agent MUST be refused, suspended, or revoked and the eligibility for licensure of any such applicant will be rescinded:

Obtaining, having, or using a license/appointment to solicit or handle controlled business;
Material misstatement, misrepresentation, or fraud in applying for the license/appointment;
Lack of qualifications, as required by Insurance Code;
Proven lack of fitness or trustworthiness to engage in the business of insurance;
Failure to pass the required license exam;
Unlawful rebating;
Fraudulent or dishonest practices when conducting business under the license/appointment issued;
Proven lack of knowledge or technical competence to transact insurance in the lines licensed/appointed;
Having been found guilty of, or pleading guilty or nolo contendere (no contest) to, a felony in any jurisdiction that involves moral turpitude and that requires punishment by imprisonment of one or more years;
Fraud or dishonesty in submitting, or assisting with the submission of, a workers’ compensation claim that contains false or misleading information about employee payroll or rate class to avoid paying the appropriate premium;
Theft, embezzlement, or misuse of funds belonging to insurers, beneficiaries, or others received when transacting business under the license/appointment;
Willful misrepresentation of, or deception pertaining to, any insurance policy to settle a claim on less favorable terms than those stated in the policy;
Violating specific conditions with respect to the settlement of viatical contracts;
Deliberate failure to comply with any order of the Department or provision of Insurance Code;
Use of the license/appointment to willfully avoid compliance with Insurance Code; and
Sale of an unregistered security that was required to be registered.
If the Department receives word that a licensee has been indicted for any of the following felonies, the license and all related appointments will be immediately suspended on a temporary basis. If the licensee is found guilty or pleads nolo contendere (no contest) to the crime during an appeal, the suspension will continue, regardless of whether convicted or a judgment is entered.

Once convicted or pleading guilty to any of the following felonies, the individual is permanently barred from applying for, or holding, an insurance license in Florida:

First degree felony;
Capital felony;
Felony involving money laundering, fraud, or embezzlement; or
Felony directly related to any activity regulated by the DFS, OIR, or OFR.
Insurance Agencies
If the following conditions exist, the license of any insurance agency will be refused, suspended, or revoked if the agency or any majority owner, partner, manager, director, officer, or other person who manages or controls the agency:

Lack of the agency of one or more qualifications for licensure;
Material misstatement, misrepresentation, or fraud in applying for the license; and
Denial, suspension, or revocation of a license to practice or conduct any regulated profession, business, or vocation related to the business of insurance in any jurisdiction of the United States.
Grounds for Discretionary Refusal, Suspension, or Revocation
Applicants, Agents, Customer Representatives, Service Representatives, MGAs
If a licensee engages in behavior that does not call for mandatory termination of a license and appointment, the Department may still deny, suspend, or revoke a license, appointment, or eligibility of a license if the Department finds that certain circumstances exist:

A condition exists and, if it had been known at the time the license/appointment was issued, the license/appointment would have been refused;
Having been found guilty of, or pleading guilty or nolo contendere (no contest) to, a felony or a crime in any jurisdiction that requires punishment by imprisonment of one or more years;
Violation of a rule or order of the Department;
Failure or refusal to pay funds due to an insurer the licensee represents;
Violation of Insurance Code, or other law pertinent to the business of insurance, took place in the course of transacting business under the license/appointment;
Engaging in unfair or deceptive acts or practices, as defined in Insurance Code, when conducting the business of insurance;
Deliberately over-insuring any property or health insurance risk;
Violation of laws prohibiting twisting;
Cheating on a license exam;
Failure to inform the Department within 30 days after being convicted of, or pleading guilty or nolo contendere to a felony or crime that requires punishment by imprisonment of one or more years;
Has been the subject of, or has had, a violation of any of the following with respect to the securities or commodities industries: administrative or regulatory decision, finding, injunction, suspension, prohibition, revocation, denial, judgment, action, or order in any jurisdiction;
Knowingly assisting another to violate any provision of Insurance Code or any order or rule of the DFS, OIR, or the Commission; or
Failure to comply with any child enforcement program.
Insurance Agencies
If an insurance agency or any majority owner, partner, manager, director, officer, or other person who manages or controls the agency engages in behavior that does not call for mandatory termination of a license and appointment, the Department may still deny, suspend, or revoke a license, appointment, or eligibility for a license if it finds that certain circumstances exist:

A condition exists and, if it had been known at the time the license/appointment was issued, the license/appointment would have been refused;
Having been found guilty of, or having pleaded guilty or nolo contendere to, a felony in any state relating to the business of insurance, regardless of whether a judgment or conviction was entered;
Knowingly employing a manager or employee who deals with the public when that person’s insurance license was suspended or revoked by the Department;
Failure to take corrective action or report a violation to the Department within 30 days after the violation is known or should have been known;
Using the agency license to avoid requirements of Insurance Code; or
Committing any of the following acts with such frequency the agency operations are hazardous to the public or other persons:
Theft, embezzlement, or misuse of funds belonging to insurers, beneficiaries, or others received when transacting business under the license/appointment;
Unlawful rebating;
Misrepresentation of, or deception pertaining to, any insurance policy
Violation of any provision of Insurance Code or other law pertaining to the business of insurance;
Violation of any order or rule of the Department;
Failure or refusal to pay funds due to an insurer the licensee represents;
Engaging in unfair or deceptive acts or practices, as defined in Insurance Code, when conducting the business of insurance;
Fraudulent or dishonest practices when conducting insurance agency activities; or
Demonstrating a lack of fitness or trustworthiness to engage in the business of insurance when conducting insurance agency activities.
Duties of Licensed vs. Unlicensed Personnel
Because most insurance transactions require the insurance professional engaging in them to be licensed, it is essential for all insurance professionals to understand precisely what activities and duties require an insurance license. Similarly, it is essential for everyone to understand the boundaries separating requirements of licensed and unlicensed personnel. The Insurance Code and Administrative Rules in Florida specify clearly what conduct is permitted by law.

Clerical employees are not considered agents or customer representatives if

They are employed by an insurance agent or agency, are paid a salary, and work full-time as a clerical employee;
The taking of insurance applications, quoting insurance, and receiving premium payments from those visiting the office is incidental to their full-time clerical duties; and
Their compensation is not tied in any way to the production of insurance applications, policies, and premiums nor does it include any commissions on business handled.
Clerical employees who are not licensed cannot

Bind insurance coverage;
Initiate contact with anyone for the purpose of soliciting insurance; or
Receive any fee or other consideration for referring prospective clients to an insurance agent if the referral is contingent in any manner upon the purchase of insurance.
Compliance
In order to be sure unlicensed personnel are not engaging in any prohibited activity, it is essential for all personnel to understand Chapter 69B-222 of Florida Administrative Code, which contains the rules and definitions pertaining to unlicensed insurance personnel.

Definitions
Incidental means activity that meets ALL of the following criteria:

All “incidental” work in terms of the amount of time the employee spends performing it is no more than 10% of the employee’s time when compared to time spent performing tasks that are not “incidental” work;
The exact amount and timing of the “incidental” work is not foreseeable; and
In terms of all work performed by all employees at the agency, the total “incidental” work performed by unlicensed personnel is no more than 10% of the total time the agency’s agents, solicitors, and customer representatives, in that office, spend performing tasks that are not “incidental” work.
If a dispute arises pertaining to whether an unlicensed employee’s work is “incidental,” as long as no evidence of abuse exists, the Department will review the agency’s operations during a 6- to 12-month period.

Example:

An employee is charged with performing prohibited activity because she spent one entire 40-hour week taking applications and giving quotes. The Department will review the employee’s activity for the 6- to 12-month period prior to the week in question.

If the employee typically spent 30 minutes per week on taking applications and quotes, and only spent the week in question doing so full-time because one of the agency’s two agents was away on vacation, the work performed during the week in question WOULD be considered “incidental.”

It is important to recognize that if the employee had performed prohibited work (in other words, selling insurance), that work would still be in violation.

Giving a quote is the simple process of collecting basic underwriting information from a party asking for a quote and referring to written underwriting guidelines that state a specific rate. When an unlicensed employee gives a quote, the employee CANNOT

Use his or her own judgment;
Give insurance advice;
Interpret policy language or provisions;
Explain any underwriting or insurance procedures;
Process insurance paperwork;
Bind insurance; or
Sign an application.
Taking an application is the process of completing a blank application form with information provided by the applicant and forwarding the application to an agent or customer representative for review and processing, the binding of insurance, policy interpretation, insurance advice, and/or explanation. When an unlicensed employee takes an application, the employee CANNOT

Use his or her own judgment;
Give insurance advice;
Interpret policy language or provisions;
Explain any underwriting or insurance procedures;
Process insurance paperwork;
Bind insurance; or
Sign an application.
Unlicensed Personnel
Lawful Activities
Unlicensed employees may perform any of the following duties at any time:

Act as switchboard operator, receptionist, secretary, but only when the sole duties involve receiving incoming calls and visitors and either taking messages or directing the calls and visitors to licensed employees;
Explain claims procedures and provide claim status, but only if doing so simply requires the unlicensed individual to read information from agency files and records; unlicensed personal CANNOT their own judgment or make any interpretations based on the records or files; and
When directed to do so by a licensed agent, solicitor, or customer representative,
Call an individual and schedule a sales/solicitation appointment for that licensed employee; or
Convey specific information as a statement made by the agent (i.e., "Agent Brown wants me to tell you the cost of your policy change is $50").
Lawful "Incidental" Activities
Unlicensed employees may perform the following duties, but only if they are performed as “incidental” to their primary duties:

Give a quote in the agent's office to those visiting the office and asking for a quote;
Take an application for insurance in the agent's office for those who have called or visited the office; or
Take an insurance premium in the agent's office. This does not include the handling of premium payments received by mailroom employees or other unlicensed employees who handle mail.
Unlicensed employees may perform these duties by telephone, but only if they are physically in the agent's office.

Unlawful Activities
Unlicensed personnel may NEVER perform the following activities:

Compare insurance products, provide advice about insurance matters or needs, or interpret insurance coverage or policies;
Bind insurance, including
For new or existing clients;
On a new, renewal, or replacement basis; or
Adding additional coverage or property to existing policies; or
Soliciting the sale of insurance in any manner, including in person or by telephone; this prohibition does not include making telephone appointments at the specific request of a specific licensed agent with a specific individual.
Penalties
If an unlicensed individual or entity violates Insurance Code by transacting insurance or engaging in insurance activities without a license, the violation is considered a third degree felony punishable by:

Imprisonment up to 5 years;
A fine up to $5,000; or
If the offender is deemed a habitual felony offender, imprisonment up to 10 years.
3. Other Requirements: Advertising
In Florida, insurers must receive approval by the Department before distributing it. When using approved advertising material, agents must use it EXACTLY as approved by the insurer because altering it may render the advertising noncompliant with the Department.

Example:

Regulators investigated an insurance agency concerning one of its advertisements. The agency had altered an insurer-approved ad and the changes violated the Insurance Code.

All insurance advertising materials and communications distributed in Florida must communicate clearly that they pertain to insurance products.

Florida law considers certain types of advertising as Unfair Methods of Competition and Unfair or Deceptive Acts. Prohibited acts and practices related to advertising include misrepresenting and falsely advertising insurance policies, which is deliberately using, issuing, or distributing an estimate, illustration, statement, sales presentation, comparison, or omission that

Misrepresents an insurance policy’s benefits, advantages, conditions, or terms;
Misrepresents an insurance policy’s dividends or share or surplus to be issued;
Makes a false or misleading statement about the dividends or shares of surplus already paid on a policy;
Uses the name or title of an insurance policy, or a class of insurance, to misrepresent the true nature of the policy;
Is purposely misleading and intended to cause another policy’s lapse, forfeit, exchange, conversion, or surrender;
Misrepresents the policy as being shares of stock or insurance company ownership interest; or 
Would mislead or cause a reasonable person to believe in error that the federal government, or a state government, backs the insurance policy or is a source of claim payment made by the policy.
False information and advertising, generally means deliberately making, publishing, distributing, or issuing to the public an advertisement, statement, or announcement that contains an untrue, deceptive, or misleading statement that pertains to the business of insurance:

In a newspaper, magazine, or other written publication;
Misrepresents an insurance policy’s dividends or share or surplus to be issued;
Over a television or radio station;
In a letter, notice, circular, pamphlet, or poster; or
In any other way.
Example:

The agent purchases an ad in the local Chamber of Commerce newsletter to generate interest of fellow Chamber members in commercial lines insurance. The agent alters the approved advertising piece provided by the insurer to make it more appealing; unfortunately, the ad contains a typographical error that illustrates the policy premium as costing far less than it is advertised to cost.

Defamation is deliberately making, publishing, distributing, or issuing a verbal or written statement that is maliciously critical of, or offensive to, any individual or entity with the purpose of causing harm or injury.

Example:

The agent harbored a grudge against a former employer, the owner of an insurance agency, for firing him. During a business networking event, the agent was overheard by several people to state that his former employer had cheated on his business tax returns for years and was being investigated by the Internal Revenue Service.

Because a number of individuals believed the agent’s statement, they cancelled their insurance with the former employer and placed their business with the agent.

Prohibited advertising gifts is giving to an insured, prospective insured, or other party an advertising gift of merchandise valued at more than $25.

Example:

One general lines insurance agent made a practice of giving coffee mugs imprinted with his name and that of his insurance agency as a gift to clients who purchased any property and casualty insurance policy. The cost of the mugs was $12 each, so this practice is not prohibited.

Free insurance is advertising “free insurance” as an incentive to buy any type of property or related services. “Free insurance” is insurance for which no identifiable or additional charge is made to the buyer of property or services or for which the identifiable or additional charge is less than the cost of insurance would be.

This prohibition does not apply to blanket disability insurance, credit life or disability insurance, or travel insurance.

Example:

Investigators learned an insurance agent’s sign was advertising “free insurance” if a client earned less than $45,000 per year. This practice is prohibited.

Florida Advertising Requirements
The state of Florida requires insurance advertisements to contain clear and unambiguous statements when advertising life insurance and annuity contracts.

The Florida Administrative Rules also require life insurance and annuity advertisements to provide clear, truthful, and adequate disclosure concerning the benefits they provide and the limitations and exclusions contained in the policies to which they refer.

Definitions
Florida law refers to several types of advertisements, specifically:

Institutional advertisement;
Invitation to inquire; and 
Invitation to contract.
The sole purpose of an institutional advertisement is to promote interest in a particular insurance company that sells life insurance and annuity contracts or in the concept of life insurance and annuity contracts. Institutional advertisements do not discuss policy terms and conditions, pricing, or particulars.

The purpose of an invitation to inquire is to encourage requests for information about life insurance and annuities. This type of advertisement is restricted to contain specific information and disclosures:

The description of coverage must be brief and can only include
A brief description of the types of loss for which coverage is provided;
The dollar amount of benefits payable; and 
The period of time during which benefits are payable;
The advertisement must contain a provision that says, essentially: "This policy has exclusions, limitations, reductions in benefits, and/or terms under which the policy may be continued or discontinued. For costs and complete details of coverage, call or write your insurance agent/insurance company;" and
The advertisement CANNOT
Use any ploy that creates unwarranted concern;
Exaggerate the policy’s benefits;
Contain premium cost; or
Violate any provision of Insurance Code.
Note: If an invitation to inquire does contain a premium cost but, otherwise, meets all requirements of an invitation to inquire, it will be considered an “invitation to contract.”

The purpose of an invitation to contract is any type of advertisement that does not meet the definitions of “institutional advertisement” or “invitation to inquire.” An invitation to contract includes agent training and education materials received by a prospective policyholder even if intended for “agent use only.”

Advertising Policy Proceeds, Premiums, and Features
Advertising in Florida cannot contain any deceptive words, phrases, or illustrations and, specifically, cannot use terms that have the ability or tendency to mislead or deceive consumers about a policy’s benefits, features, proceeds, or premiums. Invitations to contract must contain the following information:

The insurer’s name;
The agent’s name;
The policy form number;
The type of plan;
The premium amount and payment period; and
If applicable, any changes to face amounts or premiums.
An invitation to contract must disclose the following:

Any limitations that affect the policy’s basic provisions; and
Provisions applicable to the policy’s renewal, cancellation, termination, modification of benefits, losses covered, and premiums associated with age or other conditions in a manner that does not make light of them.
If an advertisement invites consumers to join an association or discretionary group, it must use a separate and distinct application form that requires separate signatures for each application, meaning the application for insurance must be a different form than the application for membership in the association or group.

If an advertisement contains a testimonial, the third-party endorsement must be genuine, represent the endorser’s opinion, apply to the policy being advertised, and be reproduced accurately. When an insurer uses such a testimonial, it is considered the insurer’s own words and opinion.

If a testimonial or endorsement is used more than a year after it was originally provided by the author, the insurer must obtain a confirmation from the author.

Testimonials and endorsements are deemed made by a spokesperson if the author:

Has a financial interest in the insurer;
Is an entity of the insurer or is owned or controlled by the insurer or its employees;
Is in a policy-making position of an insurer affiliate serving as a stockholder, director, officer, or employee; or
Is compensated, in any fashion, for making the testimonial or endorsement.
A spokesperson is considered to be soliciting insurance, and needs an insurance license, if the person performs any of the following activities:

Solicits insurance or takes insurance applications;
Engages in the business of analyzing insurance policies;
Acts as an insurance consultant; or
Performs an invitation to contract, except when performed by a company officer as permitted by law.
If an advertisement contains a spokesperson’s testimonial or endorsement, the ad must disclose the spokesperson’s financial interest in a prominent fashion, along with the fact (if applicable) that the person was compensated for making the statement.

4. Other Requirements: Recordkeeping
All agents, agencies, and customer representatives licensed in Florida are required by law to receive funds in a fiduciary capacity. This includes premiums paid, return premiums, and all other money that belongs to insurers or is received by the licensee under the license.

Funds are considered trust funds and, if received on behalf of an insurer for which the licensee is required to place them into a separate trust account. The trust account must be available for inspection and audit by the Department.

All books, accounts, and records related to the payment of insurance premiums must be kept and maintained for 3 years after a payment transaction. These books, accounts, and records may be maintained in paper, by computer, or by photocopies. The only exception to this record retention requirement is for binders issued when no policy was subsequently issued and no premium was ever collected.

Any licensee that diverts or misappropriates funds held in trust as outlined above, or deprives another party of a benefit related to those funds, commits an offense as follows:

Type of Offense	Type of Offense	Penalty
Mishandled funds up to $300	First degree misdemeanor	Imprisonment up to 1 year and/or a fine up to $1,000
Mishandled funds from $301 to $19,999	Third degree felony	Imprisonment up to 5 years and/or a fine up to $5,000
Mishandled funds from $20,000 to $99,999	
Second degree felony

Imprisonment up to 15 years and/or a fine up to $10,000
Mishandled funds from $100,000 and more	 First degree felony	Imprisonment up to 30 years and/or a fine up to $10,000
The penalties and fines for habitual felony offenders are higher than those shown above are. A habitual felony offender is a defendant who was previously convicted of any combination of two or more felonies in the state of Florida, who committed the current felony while serving a prison sentence or court-ordered supervision for a prior felony conviction, or who committed the current felony with 5 years of a prior conviction, release from prison, probation, parole, or court-ordered supervision related to a prior felony conviction.

All licensed agents must maintain records related to all insurance policies for which they transact insurance. Records must be kept in the insurance agent’s office or be readily accessible by electronic or photographic means for at least 5 years after a policy expires. These policy records include daily reports, application forms, change endorsements, and any documents signed or initialed by the insured.

