6. Florida Insurance Guaranty Association (FIGA)
The Florida Insurance Guaranty Association (FIGA) is part of a national system composed of nonprofit organizations in each state that are designed to pay specific outstanding claims of insolvent property and casualty insurers. All property and casualty insurers licensed to do business in the state of Florida must become members of FIGA and the purpose of this financial mechanism is to protect Florida policyholders and claimants from financial loss.

The Florida Insurance Guaranty Association applies to all types of direct insurance EXCEPT

Life, annuity, health, and disability insurance;
Bonding obligations, including fidelity and surety bonds;
Mortgage guaranty, financial guaranty, and other types of insurance against investment risk;
Credit insurance, vendor’s single interest (VSI) insurance, and collateral protection insurance;
Warranty service protection;
Legal expense;
Ambulance, health care, and funeral service;
Optometric, dental, and pharmaceutical service plans;
Health maintenance, prepaid health clinic, and continuing care;
Self-insurance, including any type of self-insurance fund or pool;
Ocean and wet marine insurance;
Title insurance;
Surplus lines insurance;
Insurance provided or guaranteed by the government;
Workers compensation and employers liability insurance; or
Transfer of any credit or investment risk without the transfer of insurance risk.
A member insurer is any person or entity that is licensed to transact insurance in Florida and writes any kind of insurance not exempt under law (and as shown above), including reciprocal and interinsurance contracts. An insolvent insurer is a member insurer that was authorized to transact insurance in Florida at the time the policy was written or at the time an insured event occurred, and against whom and order of liquidation with a finding of insolvency was entered by the Court under a final order.

As a condition of obtaining a certificate of authority to transact insurance in Florida, all property and casualty insurers must become members of FIGA. In addition, all member insurers must agree to reimburse FIGA for all claim payments made on their behalf if they become insolvent and are subsequently rehabilitated.

The Association is obligated to pay covered claims that exist before any of the following events:

An insurer is declared insolvent and within 30 days after it is declared insolvent;
A policy’s expiration date, if it is fewer than 30 days after the date the insurer is declared insolvent; or
The insured cancels or replaces the policy, if such action is taken within 30 days of the date the insurer is declared insolvent.
FIGA pays covered claims up to the following amounts:

Type of Benefit	Coverage Limit
All policies, after the first $100 of a covered claim
$300,000
Coverage that only applies to the damaged structure and contents insured under a homeowners policy	An additional $200,000
State law prevents policyholders from recovering under FIGA and another policy for the same loss. If a covered claim is insured by FIGA, and also by an insurer that is not insolvent, any claims paid under FIGA will be reduced by any amounts paid by the other insurer. Similarly, if a policyholder is insured by FIGA and another state’s guarantee association, the primary insurance is the association of the state in which the insured’s residence is located. However, the following exceptions exist:

Under a first party claim for damage to property with a permanent location, the association in the state in which the property is located is primary; and
Under a workers’ compensation policy, the association in the state of residence of the injured employee is primary.
If an advertisement or solicitation of insurance refers to FIGA as part of the sales process, it must also spell out the coverage limits provided by the Association.

Insurance Laws and Updates
1. Federal Law Updates
Department of Labor Fiduciary Rule
Qualified retirement plans, such as 401(k) plans, IRAs, are critical to the retirement security of many U.S. workers. Investment professionals play an important role in guiding these investment decisions. However, the ways that financial advisers are compensated sometimes create conflicts of interest, which can bias the investment advice they give and impact customer investment results. The Department of Labor has proposed a new rule that attaches fiduciary status to more of the advice rendered to plan officials, participants, and beneficiaries.

The Department of Labor's (DOL) Conflict of Interest Rule, also known as the fiduciary rule, would change how a financial professional becomes a fiduciary under the Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA), and establishes a new set of standards for everyone doing business in the qualified marketplace. The rule would require additional disclosures, documentation, supervision and a host of new rules and regulations.

Under the new rule, insurance-only agents who want to receive compensation on new business may need to work with a financial institution, which will vouch that the agent is working in the client's best interest. Financial institutions include:

Broker/dealers registered with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC);
Banks;
Insurance companies;
Registered investment advisers (RIAs).
Independent, life insurance only agents who work within the qualified marketplace may decide to become registered representatives or investment advisor representatives, may become full fiduciaries by registering with the SEC, or may abandon the qualified market altogether.

The status of this new rule has been somewhat in limbo since the 2016 election. The new Administration has delayed implementation and may cancel it altogether. Still, many financial institutions have already adopted these fiduciary best practices.

National Flood Insurance Program
Floods are generally caused by a variety of weather events; therefore, virtually all property is exposed to the risk of being inundated by floodwaters. Because insurable perils must be accidental in nature, and not likely or certain to occur, standard property insurers have traditionally excluded the peril of flood from coverage provided by their policies. In the current marketplace, virtually every property policy excludes the peril of flood.

Over time, the combination of an historical increase in the occurrence of damaging floods and the lack of available insurance placed a tremendous financial burden on the U.S. government and its citizens and businesses, all of whom shouldered the cost of uninsured flood damage after catastrophic events in this country.

Attempts were made to reduce the potential for flood-induced property damage by constructing dams, levees, and other structures to divert floodwaters from buildings, farmlands, and communities.

However, when a rise in the number of natural disasters occurred during the 1950s and 1960s, the U.S. government decided additional measures were required to supplement the structural controls upon which the country relied.

FLOOD FACTS

The number one natural disaster in the United States is flooding.
Over the term of a 30-year mortgage, property located in a high-risk flood area is more apt to sustain flood damage than it is to sustain fire damage.
More than 20% of all NFIP flood insurance claims are for property that is NOT located in a high-risk flood zone (i.e., it is located in moderate- or low-risk areas).
The average flood insurance premium is approximately $700 per year; the average flood insurance claim during the past 5 years was almost $42,000.
Between 2008 and 2012, the average NFIP commercial flood insurance claim exceeded $87,000.
Between 2010 and 2014, the average of all NFIP flood insurance claims was almost $42,000.
Between 2005 and 2014 the total amount paid for NFIP flood insurance claims exceeded $3.5 billion, per year.
In calendar year 2014, NFIP flood insurance policies paid more than $345 million in claims to policyholders.
The state of Florida received the highest amount of NFIP claim payments among the states (2,655 claims for total payments of $117,861,100).
Source: Federal Emergency Management Agency, 2015
National Flood Insurance Program
When the National Flood Insurance Act (NFIA) was passed by Congress in 1968, the National Flood Insurance Program was created to establish a nationwide floodplain management mechanism that would accomplish two goals:

Reduce property damage caused by floods; and
Reduce government and public spending in the form of disaster assistance.
Flood insurance was made available to the public for the first time, and over the years, the NFIA was amended by subsequent federal legislations:

The Flood Insurance Protection Act of 1973 and Flood Disaster Protection Act of 1973 required lenders of federally backed loans and mortgages to require the issuance of flood insurance on property secured by those loans if it is located in a high-risk flood area (Special Flood Hazard Area, or SFHA).

The National Flood Insurance Reform Act of 1984 increased the focus on compliance by lenders and created a mitigation assistance program to reduce the costs of flood damage.

The Flood Insurance Reform Act of 2004 (FIRA) established minimum flood insurance training and education requirements for insurance agents and created other NFIP reforms pertaining to repetitive loss properties and consumer awareness.

The Biggert-Waters Flood Insurance Reform Act of 2012 funded and implemented a national remapping program along with certain rate increases to strengthen the fiscal soundness of the NFIP. These rate increases were designed to eliminate discounted flood insurance rates and require NFIP policies to charge the full actuarial rates of flood risk.

The Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2014 prevented certain provisions of Biggert-Waters from being implemented (i.e., elimination of subsidized rates and grandfathering provisions) while Congress negotiated the drafting of new flood insurance laws.

The Homeowner Flood Insurance Affordability Act of 2014 was the result of Congressional and public disappointment with Biggert-Waters and the Consolidated Appropriations Act. It repealed certain sections of Biggert-Waters, restored the NFIP’s grandfathering provisions, established limits on certain rate increases, and applied an annual policy surcharge on all policies to address commitment to the NFIP’s continued fiscal soundness.

The NFIP is administered by the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), which is an agency of the U.S. Department of Homeland Security, and works with nearly 80 private insurance companies in its Write Your Own (WYO) Program. WYO carriers work in cooperation with the federal government to write and service the NFIP’s Standard Flood Insurance Policy (SFIP) in their own names. The carriers must comply with the NFIP’s rules and regulations in exchange for receiving an expense allowance for policies written and claims processed.

The WYO Program has 3 main goals:

Increase the number and geographic distribution of NFIP policies;
Improve service to NFIP policyholders; and
Provide the insurance industry with direct flood insurance operating experience.
The NFIP is scheduled to continue through September 2017; however, reauthorization of the Program has involved some challenges in the past.

Since 2008, the NFIP was reauthorized by public law 18 times; at four of those times, the Program actually lapsed and no flood insurance was permitted to be issued or renewed during the terms of the lapses. Although three of the lapses only lasted for 1 day, the NFIP was actually suspended for 2 months during 2010, from May 31 through June 1.

Because the financial condition of the NFIP had been tenuous for some time, when Congress enacted Biggert-Waters, it eliminated the NFIP’s Grandfather Rule for most policies issued with subsidized rates as a means to help strengthen its fiscal condition. Biggert-Waters called for policyholders to pay the “full-risk rate” for flood insurance and capped annual premium rate increases at 25% until the full-risk rate was achieved. (Note: the full-risk rate is the actuarial charge for insurance, without subsidies, based on the property’s actual flood risk.)

A great many politicians and consumers created public outcry, denouncing Biggert-Waters’ premium increases, along with several other of its provisions. As a result, Congress enacted the HFIAA to

Lower some of Biggert-Waters’ rate increases;
Prevent some of Biggert-Waters’ future rate increases;
Implement a surcharge (beginning in 2015) that applies to all flood policies; and
Repeal certain Biggert-Waters rate increases that were already implemented, providing for refunds to those policyholders affected.
Grandfathering Rule
The NFIP’s Grandfathering Rule allows certain property owners to obtain flood insurance at subsidized rates under specific circumstances after a flood insurance rate map (FIRM) has been revised or republished. Grandfathering applies when the property is remapped into a higher flood zone.

Before enactment of Biggert-Waters and HFIAA, any type of property was eligible for grandfathering if

The policyholder had maintained continuous coverage under the NFIP flood insurance policy; or
The building was constructed in accordance with the flood insurance rate map at the time of construction.
FEMA began updating this country’s flood insurance rate maps (FIRMs) in 2008. Earlier versions of FIRMs were at least 10 years old and did not reflect the latest data-gathering and mapping technology. Sometimes, after a new FIRM is issued, some property owners find that their property has been remapped into a different flood hazard zone. If the new flood zone is lower than the original zone, it generates a lower premium and property owners tend to be happy.

Unfortunately, if property is remapped into a higher zone, especially into a high-risk flood zone from a low- or moderate-risk zone, property owners are not happy when they experience a rate increase.

In other circumstances, remapping results in

The base flood elevation increasing for certain pieces of property, which also generates a premium increase; and
A federal mandate for a property owner to purchase flood insurance, if the new flood zone is in a SFHA and the property was secured by a federally regulated or insurance mortgage or loan.
A high-risk flood zone is referred to as Special Flood Hazard Area (SFHA); property located in a SFHA has a 25 percent chance of experiencing a base flood during the term of a 30-year mortgage. If property located in a SFHA was purchased in connection with a mortgage or loan provided by a federally regulated or insured lender, FEMA requires the property owner to purchase flood insurance.

The base flood elevation is the elevation shown on a FIRM for SFHAs; it indicates the water surface elevation resulting from a base flood, which is a flood that has a 1% change of equaling or exceeding that level in any given year. A base flood is the standard used by the NFIP, FEMA, and all federal agencies.

It is important for agents to understand that property owners with property remapped into a SFHA only have one opportunity to take advantage of the Grandfather Rule.
Currently, grandfathering is ONLY available for buildings that are the primary residences of their owners and

The property owner had already purchased a NFIP flood insurance policy when the new flood insurance rate map became effective; or
The building was constructed in compliance with the FIRM in effect at the time of construction.
Buildings that have been substantially damaged or improved are NOT eligible for grandfathering.
Refunds
Because certain provisions of Biggert-Waters were repealed by the HFIAA, some flood insurance policyholders paid increased premium rates that are no longer legal. The NFIP and the WYO insurers are required to provide refunds to these policyholders.

The following charge provides details of policies eligible for refunds:

New Policies for Pre-FIRM Buildings
Requirements:

Must be in flood zones A, D, or V;
Building must have been constructed before the effective date of the first FIRM;
Building cannot have been substantially damaged or improved; and
Policy effective date is on or after 10/01/2013.
If eligible, the policyholder MAY receive a one-time refund that will equal the difference between the full-risk rate paid and the subsidized rate that went into effect on 10/01/2013.

Only about 1% of all NFIP policies are eligible for this refund.

Pre-FIRM Buildings: Policies Reinstated after Lapse
Requirements:

Must be in flood zones A, D, or V;
Building must have been constructed before the effective date of the first FIRM;
Building cannot have been substantially damaged or improved; and
Policy effective date is on or after 10/04/2012.
If eligible, the policyholder MAY receive a one-time refund that will equal the difference between the full-risk rate paid and the subsidized rate that went into effect on 10/01/2013.

Future subsidized rates will ONLY apply if the reinstatement occurs after coverage was dropped because the lender no longer required coverage.

Pre-FIRM Buildings: 25% Rate Increase for Nonresidential Buildings
Requirements:

Must be in flood zones A, D, or V; and
Policyholder received a 25% increase at renewal on or after 10/01/2013.
If eligible, the policyholder MAY receive a one-time refund if the premium increase was more than 18%.

Rate Increases of More than 18% for Other Residential and Nonresidential Buildings
If the policy rate increased more than 18% at renewal on or after 10/01/2013 and the building does not fall into an exception category (see below).

If eligible, the policyholder MAY receive a one-time refund of the difference between the higher rate paid and the maximum 18% cap.

Only about 13% of all NFIP policies are eligible for this refund

Policies with premium increases that are NOT eligible for refunds include the following:

Policy was in effect before 07/06/2012 and building is a Pre-FIRM non-primary residence;
Premium increases will continue at 25% until the full-risk rate is achieved;
Policy was in effect before 07/06/2012 and the building is a severe repetitive loss property;
Premium increases will continue at 25% until the full-risk rate is achieved;
Premium increase was the result of a reduction in the deductible or an increase in the limit or type of coverage; or
Not eligible for any type of refund.
All refunds will be mailed to the policyholder and only apply to increases in premiums.
HFIAA - April 2015 Program Changes
In April 2015, implementation of the HFIAA began taking place for both new business flood insurance policies and renewal flood insurance policies issued by the NFIP and insurers participating in its Write Your Own Program.

Premium Increases and Surcharges
Beginning in April 2015, average annual increases in premium rates, by risk class, are capped at 15%. These increases also require the average increase for all subsidized policies insuring Pre-FIRM buildings (those constructed before the community’s first FIRM was issued) to be at least 5%.

Most individual policies cannot experience an annual rate increase in excess of 18%, unless an exception exists. Exceptions exist for the following types of property, and the annual premium rate increase is capped at 25% per year:

Non-primary residences (i.e., secondary homes, seasonal dwellings, homes rented to others, apartment buildings);
Severe repetitive loss properties (primary residences that have sustained damage at least twice and for which claims have been submitted to the NFIP that meet certain criteria);
Buildings that have been substantially damaged or improved; and
Beginning in 2016, the 25% premium rate cap will apply to commercial buildings.
An annual surcharge now applies to all flood insurance policies issued by the NFIP and its WYO insurers. The purpose of the surcharge is to offset the subsidies provided by NFIP’s Grandfather Rule and support the NFIP’s financial stability. The annual surcharge is paid at the time of application for a new policy and at each renewal thereafter; it will be collected until all subsidies are eliminated.

The surcharge per policy is $25 for primary residences insured on a Dwelling Form and $250 for all other types of buildings. Insurers are required to verify a building’s status as a primary residence before applying the $25 surcharge.

In order to receive the $25 surcharge instead of the $250 surcharge, the policyholder or agent must submit a statement to the insurer with a Verification of Primary Residence Form.

The verification form requires one of the following documents to be submitted along with it:

Driver’s license;
Auto registration;
Proof of vehicle insurance;
Voter registration;
Homestead tax credit form for primary residence; or
A document that shows where children attend school.
Failure to submit the form within 30 days of the date the form is mailed by the insurer to the insured will result in the $250 surcharge being issued on the renewal policy.

Eligibility for the $25 surcharge is explicit. The building must be

An owner-occupied, single-family, detached residence, or an individual condominium; and
The policyholder’s primary residence.
Because a flood insurance policy is issued with the annual surcharge, the probation surcharge, and the Federal Policy Fee (these surcharges and fees are not considered part of the premium), the actual increase in the amount a policyholder must pay may increase more than 18%. Because the surcharge is not considered a premium, it is not subject to a cap or limitation.

Building Use Questionnaire
Agents must be sure to confirm the use of an insured building prior to renewal to be sure the policyholder is charged the appropriate rate increase and annual surcharge. The NFIP Building Use Questionnaire can be completed by either the policyholder or the agent to determine whether the policy insures a nonresidential business property, or other nonresidential property. Implementation of this identification process is November 1, 2015 and the associated premium rate increases will begin in the spring of 2016.

The following information requires verification:

Is the building a non-residential business building or another non-residential building?
Is the building’s purpose mixed use and, if so, what are the percentages of use? 
Is the insured a small business with fewer than 100 employees?
Is the insured a nonprofit organization?
Is the insured building a house of worship?
Is the insured building an agricultural structure?
The NFIP considers a building to be a “business” building if a licensed commercial enterprise operates to generate income and the policy provides insurance for one of the following:

A building designed for use as a non-habitational building;
A mixed-use building in which the total floor area devoted to commercial use is more than 25% of the total floor area in the building; or
A building designed for use as an office, retail or wholesale space, hospitality area, and/or similar uses.
The NFIP considers a building to be an “other nonresidential” building if it is used for non-habitational or mixed-use purposes that do not qualify the building as a residential building or nonresidential “business” building.

25% Rate Increases
Annual rate increases of 25% apply to non-primary residences and properties that experience severe repetitive loss. The increases apply on a rate class basis and not to individual policies. The annual 25% rate increase will continue until the full-risk rate is achieved. On occasion, a policy will renew and, afterward, will become a severe repetitive loss property or a non-primary residence and may experience a premium rate increase in excess of 25%. This condition is considered a “misrating” and is considered an exception to the mandated annual rate caps of 18% and 25%.

Buildings that have been substantially damaged or improved will also experience annual premium rate increases of 25% until they have achieved the full-risk rate.

Reserve Fund Assessment
The Reserve Fund Assessment that was enacted under Biggert-Waters will be phased in over time to comply with the 15% cap on average annual premium increases. It has been increased to 15% for all policies except Preferred Risk Policies (PRPs), for which it will be 10%.

Federal Policy Fee (FPF)
The Federal Policy Fee (FPF) remains at $22 for Preferred Risk Policies, but increased for all other policies except Residential Condominium Building Association Policies (RCBAPs). The new $45 FPF will apply to policies that were rated previously under the PRP Extension (which are now rated under Properties Newly Mapped into the SFHA and will be discussed later), and policies effective on or after 04/01/2015 that insure buildings newly mapped into a SFHA by a map revision effective on or after March 21, 2014 (the date the HFIAA was enacted).

The annual FPFs for RCBAPs per policy are as follows:

$45 for a single-unit building;
$135 for a building with 2 to 4 units;
$360 for a building with 5 to 10 units;
$720 for a building with 11 to 20 units; and
$1,800 for a building with more than 20 units.
Deductibles
Under the HFIAA, the maximum deductible for policies insuring residential buildings was increased to $10,000. However, when a policyholder chooses this deductible, it must apply to both building and contents.

Minimum deductibles for PRPs and Mortgage Portfolio Protection Program policies are $1,000 for both building and contents if the building limit of insurance is no more than $100,000. If the building limit of insurance is more than $100,000, the minimum deductible is $1,250.

Grandfathering
The HFIAA restored grandfathering under certain conditions. Current eligibility requires a building to be newly mapped into a SFHA after a map revision. In this circumstance, the policy will receive a “preferred risk premium” only for the year following the map revision. Thereafter, the policy’s premium rates will be subject to the annual premium rate increase caps that apply to other policies. Beginning on the first renewal, these policies must be rated using the newly created rate tables for Property Newly Mapped into the SFHA.

If a property owner does not have flood insurance in place on a building that is being newly mapped into an SFHA, the owner MUST purchase flood insurance before the date the new map becomes effective in order to be eligible for grandfathering.

2. New Florida Law Updates
Flood Insurance
According to the OIR, the state of Florida pays four times more into the NFIP than it receives in claim payments and is the state with the largest number of NFIP policyholders. Due to the potential negative effects of flood insurance pricing increases resulting from enactment of Biggert-Waters and the HFIAA, the Florida Legislature enacted Senate Bill 542 to facilitate the writing of flood insurance in Florida by private insurance companies.

This process offers consumers with an alternative to purchasing flood insurance from the NFIP and its WYO carriers; it also provides different types of flood insurance.

