Florida Insurance Commissioner's Press Release: April 1, 2015

A growing number of private insurers are now writing flood insurance in Florida; some are offering coverage at pricing lower than that offered by the NFIP.
NFIP premiums for Florida policyholders may increase by up to 18% due to changes relating to the enactment of the HFIAA.
In 2014, the average premium for a NFIP flood insurance policy in Florida was $529.
In 2014, the average NFIP flood insurance claim in Florida was $22,251.
The enactment of Senate Bill 542 streamlines the process for private insurers to write flood insurance in Florida, provides an alternative to the NFIP, and allows three different types of flood insurance to be offered by private insurers-all of which began with the basic coverage provided by the standard flood insurance policy offered by the NFIP.
Outcome of Senate Bill 542
When the OIR reviews certain insurer rate filings, projected flood losses have been added to the factors it must consider. In addition, the Commission must adopt actuarial methods, principals, standards, and/or models for personal lines residential flood loss no later than July 2017.

A new section of the Florida Insurance Code now permits authorized insurers to issue personal lines residential policies that insure against the peril of flood on any structure or its personal property. This new law does not apply to any type of commercial lines property coverage insuring against the peril of flood (including residential) or excess flood insurance. When issuing personal lines flood insurance, carriers may do so on a standard, preferred, customized, or supplemental basis.

When issuing standard flood insurance, coverage can only be provided for the peril of flood (as defined below) that is substantially the same as coverage provided by the NFIP’s standard flood insurance policy. Standard flood insurance issued by private insurers in Florida must also provide the same deductibles and loss adjustment methods provided by the NFIP’s standard flood insurance policy.

When issuing preferred flood insurance, coverage must be provided on the same basis as a standard flood insurance policy; however, it may also

Include in the definition of flood losses from water intrusion that originates from outside the insured structure that are not otherwise covered under the policy’s definition of flood;
Include coverage for additional living expense (this coverage is NOT provided by any of the NFIP’s flood policies); and
Require that any losses for personal property (contents) that are repaired or replaced only be adjusted on a replacement cost basis up to the policy’s limits.
When issuing customized flood insurance, coverage must be broader than that provided under standard flood insurance.

When issuing flexible flood insurance, coverage may be issued on the same basis as standard or preferred flood insurance; however, it must also include one or more of the following provisions:

An agreement between the insurance company and insured that flood insurance is issued in a specified amount (i.e., limited to the total amount of an outstanding mortgage on the insured property);
A requirement for a deductible in an amount permitted by law (under §627.701 Liability of Insureds, Coinsurance, Deductibles), including a hurricane deductible;
A requirement that a flood loss to a dwelling is adjusted on a replacement cost basis in accordance with Insurance Code (under §626.7011(3)) or only on the basis of the property’s actual cash value;
A restriction that limits flood insurance to the principal building defined in the policy;
A provision that either includes or excludes coverage for additional living expenses; or
A provision that excludes coverage for personal property (contents) against the peril of flood.
When issuing supplemental flood insurance, coverage must be designed to supplement coverage provided by either

The NFIP’s standard flood insurance policy; or
Standard or preferred flood insurance issued by a private insurer in Florida.
However, supplemental flood insurance is not required to (but may) provide coverage for jewelry, art, deductibles, and additional living expenses.

Under Florida law, the definition of flood is the same as the definition contained in the NFIP’s policies:

Flood means a general and temporary condition of partial or complete inundation of two or more acres of normally dry land area or of two or more properties, at least one of which is the policyholder’s property, from

Overflow of inland or tidal waters;
Unusual and rapid accumulation or runoff of surface waters from any source;
Mudflow; or
Collapse or subsidence of land along the shore of a lake or similar body of water as a result of erosion or undermining caused by waves or currents of water exceeding anticipated cyclical levels that result in a flood as defined in this paragraph.
Other requirements of the newly enacted insurance laws pertaining to flood insurance include:

All policy limits of insurance and deductibles must be displayed prominently on the policy’s Declarations page;
Surplus lines agents may export flood insurance policies or endorsements to eligible surplus lines insurers without making a diligent effort to obtain coverage from three or more insurers, as typically required;
Insurers providing private flood insurance in Florida must, in addition to other applicable requirements notify the OIR, at least 30 days in advance, before writing flood insurance in Florida;
Requiring an agent to offer a flood insurance quote when quoting an insurance policy that will cover a residential structure located within a special flood hazard area;
Requiring the agent to maintain a record of an insured's declination of flood insurance coverage for a period of 36 months;
Revising the notice that must be provided to and acknowledged by an applicant for flood coverage from an authorized or surplus lines insurer if the applicant's property is receiving flood insurance under the National Flood Insurance Program;
Allowing an authorized insurer to request a certification from the Office of Insurance Regulation which indicates that a policy, contract, or endorsement issued by the insurer provides coverage for the peril of flood which equals or exceeds the flood coverage offered by the National Flood Insurance Program;
Authorizing the insurer receiving such a certificate or its agent to reference or include the certification in specified advertising, communications, and documentation; and
Requiring that if the Office of Insurance Regulation (Office) finds flood rates are excessive or unfairly discriminatory, the Office must appropriately credit existing policyholders or refund those not still insured by the insurer.
The following entities may NOT provide insurance for the peril of flood:

Citizens Property Insurance Corporation; and
The Florida Hurricane Catastrophe Fund.
Any insurance company or agent who knowingly misrepresents that a flood insurance policy, contract, or endorsement is certified as such under Florida Insurance Code is guilty of committing an unfair method of competition or an unfair or deceptive act.

Eligibility for Coverage by Citizens Property Insurance Corporation
NFIP underwriting guidelines usually prohibit the issuance of flood insurance on property located within the Coastal Barrier Resources System (CBRS). In addition, state law prohibits Citizens Property Insurance Corporation (Citizens) from insuring a “major structure” that has been newly constructed or substantially improved if it is located seaward of the coastal construction control line or within the CBRS.

A major structure is defined by Florida law to be a house, mobile home, apartment building, condominium, motel, hotel, restaurant, tower, other types of buildings (including residential, commercial, or public), and other construction that has the potential for substantial impact on coastal zones. A substantial improvement in Florida is interpreted to mean any repair, reconstruction, rehabilitation, or improvement to a structure that costs 50% or more of the structure’s market value.

House Bill 715; effective July 1, 2015; Amends §§627.351 and 627.712, F.S.: This new piece of legislation replaces former legislation that prohibited the issuance of insurance a major structure that was substantially improved after obtaining a building permit that was applied for on or after July 1, 2015, with a prohibition that states coverage cannot be issued on a structure that is "rebuilt, repaired, restored, or remodeled to increase the total square footage of finished area by more than 25%" based on a building permit applied for after July 1, 2015.
NFIP Elevation Certificate Records
The Florida legislature passed and the governor signed into law Senate Bill 1094 with an effective date of July 1, 2015. This Bill modifies several sections of Florida statute related to flood insurance.

We have already discussed the changes this Bill made to 627.715, F.S. which directly affect the Insurance Code, but other sections of this Bill, while not directly related to Florida Insurance Code, address the peril of flood from a land use and insurance standpoint. Senate Bill 1094 also amended 163.3178, F.S. to require the redevelopment component of the coastal management element of local government comprehensive plans to do the following:

Include development and redevelopment principles, strategies, and engineering solutions that reduce the flood risk in coastal areas;
Encourage the use of best practices and identify site development techniques to reduce flood losses;
Be consistent with or more stringent than flood-resistant construction techniques in the Florida Building Code and applicable federal flood plain management regulations; and
Encourage local governments to participate in the federal flood insurance program community rating system.
Senate Bill 1094 also created 195.088, F.S. which, beginning January 1, 2017, requires appraisers, surveyors, and mappers to provide the Division of Emergency Management with a copy of each federal flood insurance program elevation certificate completed within 30 days of completion. The appraisers, surveyors, and mappers may redact the name of the property owner from the elevation certificate prior to submission to the Division of Emergency Management. These sections of Senate Bill 1094 seek to mitigate flooding risk, gather additional flood hazard mapping data through elevation certificates and increase participation in the NFIP community rating system.

Other P&C Insurance Changes in 2015
Residential Property Insurance – Advance Notice of Cancellation
Insurance companies that issue residential property insurance are now required to provide 120 days' advance written notice of nonrenewal, cancellation, or termination, regardless of the reason or when the policy is being terminated. Prior law called for 100 days’ advance written notice, which was subject to other conditions based on the policy’s termination date.

Motor Vehicle Insurance
Pre-Inspection Requirement: Florida law requires insurers to inspect private passenger motor vehicles before issuing physical damage coverage, including collision and comprehensive coverages. An exemption to this requirement exists for an insured who has had insurance in place continuously for at least two years if the agent verifies the existence of the prior coverage and the fact that it was not interrupted. New legislation extends this exemption to “any” vehicle, not just private passenger vehicles.

The new law also allows leased vehicles to be exempt from pre-inspection requirements. Insurance companies have the option of electing to require the submission of certain documents when issuing coverage without requiring a pre-inspection. The vehicle’s dealer invoice is no longer one of the documents the insurer may require; however, the vehicle’s registration has been added to the list of documents the insurer may require. The processes of issuing claim reimbursements and suspending physical damage coverage are now based upon when the supporting documents are delivered to the insurer.

House Bill 4011; effective July 1, 2015; Amends §§627.041 and 627.728: Before enactment of this law, private passenger auto insurance policies were limited to provide coverage for no more than 4 vehicles per policy. If a consumer owned more than 4 vehicles, they were required to obtain additional policies in sufficient number to comply with this requirement.

Upon enactment of House Bill 4011, insurance companies may issue private passenger auto insurance policies that insure any number of private passenger motor vehicles. To effect this outcome, the law removed the 4-vehicle maximum from the insurance law rating definition of motor vehicle insurance, and from the regulatory definition of policy.

Ethical Requirements
1. Ethical Code
Florida insurance laws and rules contain requirements that specify how the Department will apply ethical standards of conduct to the manner in which licensed insurance agents interact with other agents, insurance companies, and the public.

NAIFA Code of Ethics
Preamble

Helping my clients protect their assets and establish financial security, independence, and economic freedom for themselves and those they care about is a noble endeavor and deserves my promise to support high standards of integrity, trust, and professionalism throughout my career as an insurance and financial professional. With these principles as a foundation, I freely accept the following obligations:

To help maintain my clients’ confidences and protect their right to privacy.
To work diligently to satisfy the needs of my clients.
To present, accurately and honestly, all facts essential to my clients’ financial decisions.
To render timely and proper service to my clients and ultimately their beneficiaries.
To continually enhance professionalism by developing my skills and increasing my knowledge through education.
To obey the letter and spirit of all laws and regulations which govern my profession. 
To conduct all business dealings in a manner which would reflect favorably on NAIFA and my profession.
To cooperate with others whose services best promote the interests of my clients.
To protect the financial interests of my clients, their financial products and my profession, through political advocacy.
Adopted July 2012, NAIFA Board of Trustees

When adhering to a universal code of ethics, agents working in the insurance industry in this state are more likely to comply with state law, present themselves to the public as a member of a cohesive unit, one that works in partnership with other members of the insurance and business communities, and exhibit behavior that displays professionalism and encourages trust and confidence.

Use of Insurance Designations
A professional designation is a certification that its designee has undertaken specialized education and training in his or her field. Some designations are very specific and focus on a single, specific topic, such as the Associate in Risk Management (ARM) designation. The focus of other designations is broader and more comprehensive, such as the Chartered Property Casualty Underwriter (CPCU) designation, which certifies the designee’s knowledge and expertise the property and casualty segment of the insurance industry, including the areas of insurance operations, business law, finance and accounting, commercial property and liability risk management, personal insurance, personal risk management, and financial planning. The CPCU designation also requires designees to pass a 50-question exam on ethics.

Unfortunately, some insurance agents claim to have expertise that they have not, in fact, acquired. Because this misuse of designations often harms consumers, many states have enacted laws specific to it the misuse of designations. Some such state legislation only addresses misuse pertaining to seniors or particular lines of insurance (i.e. life insurance); however, Florida’s laws pertaining to the use of designations apply to “the marketing, solicitation, negotiation, sale or advice made in connection with an insurance transaction by any licensee.”

Although numerous professional insurance designations can be attained, the Florida Department of Financial Services does not endorse any of them; it does, however, have specific definitions for the phrases "designation" and "certification."

Designation

Any combination of words, any acronym standing for a combination of words, or any job title that indicates or implies that a licensee has special knowledge or training in advising or servicing consumers beyond the knowledge or training required for the license held.

Certification

Any designation that indicates, implies, or recognizes that an individual or organization meets certain established criteria beyond the criteria required for the license held.

Examples of professional insurance designations include

Certified Insurance Counselor (CIC): Pertains to expertise in personal lines, commercial property, commercial casualty, life and health, agency management, and risk management;
Accredited Advisor in Insurance (AAI): Pertains to all aspects of the property and casualty segment of the insurance industry, and specifically underwriting, commercial and personal lines, agency management, and customer service; and
Certified Risk Manager (CRM): Pertains to identifying, analyzing, controlling, financing, and administering organizational risks.
Examples of professional insurance designations include

Certified Insurance Service Representative (CISR): Focuses on nine areas within the insurance industry and each certificant must take and pass the exam for five of the nine courses within a 5-year period; and
Accredited Advisor in Insurance (ACSR): Similar to the CISR certification, this certification does not require an annual update but does allow the certificant to specialize in commercial lines, personal lines, or life and health insurance.
In Florida, it is a violation of Insurance Code for any individual to use an insurance designation or certification unless it was obtained from a professional organization with published standards and procedures for pledging the degree of expertise of those awarded the designation or certification. Specifically, the standards and procedures must be used and enforced regularly by the organization and must address specific subject matters. In addition, the organization must approve the use of its name, logo, trademark, or other marketing images and labels used by its designees and certificants.

Four specific prohibitions apply to the use of designations in Florida:

Using a designation for which an individual is not eligible or has not actually earned;
Using a nonexistent designation or one designed or created by the individual himself or herself;
Using a designation that was not acquired in compliance with the standards and procedures of the organization conferring it; and
Stating or implying that the individual has acquired a degree of expertise or qualifications through education, training, or experience that he or she has not actually acquired.
Obligations for Reporting Unlicensed Insurance Activity
Unlicensed insurance activity takes place when the person or insurance plan transacting insurance does not hold the appropriate Florida license to do so, including self-insurers. An exception exists for entities authorized to self-insure under the Workers Compensation Law. Those required to hold insurance licenses in this state include insurance companies, managed care entities, agents, sales representatives, sales agents, salespersons, runners, bail bondsmen, brokers, third-party administrators, and adjusters.

All insurance licensees are required by Florida law to notify the Department of information relating to any unlicensed insurance activity taking place in this state if and when they become aware of it. Information that must be reported includes (if known):

Organizational information about the unlicensed entity;
Information about any insurance benefits or contracts being offered by the unlicensed entity, including reinsurance;
The names, addresses, and telephone numbers of any officers or agents of the unlicensed entity; and
The names, addresses, and telephone numbers of any of the unlicensed entity’s employers, employees, enrolled individuals, or individuals who are or may be receiving services.
The most common types of entities engaging in unlicensed insurance activity in Florida are reportable Multiple Employer Welfare Arrangements (MEWAs), employee leasing arrangements, welfare benefits plans, and collectively bargained arrangement. By definition under Florida Administrative Code, an arrangement is a fund, trust, plan, instrument, program, association, union, or other entity or mechanism that provides for the transfer of the risk of loss, damage, or expense resulting from a fortuitous event to another.

All information should be reported the Department at Unlicensed Entity Coordinator, Florida Department of Financial Services, Division of Investigative and Forensic Services (formerly Division of Insurance Fraud). The report can be made by telephone (850-413-4000) or by mail to 2020 Capital Circle, S. E., Alexander Building, Tallahassee, FL 32301.

2. Unfair Trade Practices
The distinction between illegal and unethical is not always clear. When human beings behave in an ethical fashion, they do what is good, right, and proper, as determined by the society or business industry in which they live. However, what society views as good, right, and proper changes over time and based upon circumstances.

Until the early 1900s, very few insurance laws were on the books. However, when a New York journalist charged a number of life insurance companies with using company funds to spend excessively and make political payoffs over a period of several in the early 1900s, the superintendent of the New York Department of Insurance began an investigation in 1905. The New York legislature established a special committee led by Senator Armstrong (the Armstrong Committee), which eventually found the following unethical practices were being conducted by the Equitable Life Assurance Society:

Creating subsidiaries to dodge restrictions on investments;
Proxy voting to interfere with policyholder control of mutual insurance companies;
Allowing members of its Board of Directors to serve on the board of directors of multiple companies;
Incurring lavish company expenses;
Spending far more on lobbying activities than its competitors;
Rebating;
Encouragement of policy lapses to write new insurance; and
Encouraging twisting.
Although several other insurers were found to have committed incidents of unethical conduct, none was publicized as extensively as Equitable was. Because of the Armstrong Committee’s findings, the state of New York enacted insurance legislation in 1907; this action was followed by other states after they conducted their own investigations. Many of the laws passed by New York were considered overly strict by many in the industry; however, they were necessary for the protection of the policyholders. These included

Prohibition against preferred dividend policies and the requirement that policyholders be paid regular dividends;
Regulations that stipulated what investments were “acceptable”;
Limits on campaign contributions and lobbying activity;
Elimination of proxy voting;
Standardizing policy forms; and
Limiting agent activity by outlawing certain practices such as rebating and twisting.
Traditionally, the majority of the insurance industry’s regulation in the United States has taken place at the state level. However, in 1944, litigation occurred that challenged the states’ authority with respect to how insurers conducted business across state lines (i.e., as acts of interstate commerce).

As a result of landmark litigation that was heard by the Supreme Court (United States v. South-Eastern Underwriters Association), the McCarran-Ferguson Act became law in 1945 and stipulates that the federal government can only regulate the business of insurance to the extent one or more of the states do not regulate it. A notable exception to McCarran-Ferguson is the federal government’s jurisdiction over antitrust issues such as boycott, coercion, and intimidation.

Restraint of Trade
In order to understand why the states regulate the business practices of insurance companies, agents, and other licensees, it is important to possess an overall understanding of how business operations affect the economy of our country. One of the most harmful business endeavors to a society is a monopoly.

A monopoly is a single entity that owns and controls the majority of the marketplace for a specific product or service. By its nature, a monopoly eliminates competition, which, in turn, generally results in an increase in prices and a decrease in the quality of the product or service being provided. While beneficial to the owners of a monopoly, monopolistic practices seldom benefit others, especially consumers. Some argue that when big business is not permitted to control a market, more issues arise for consumers because smaller businesses do not have the ability to provide the same high quality of products and services, or access to them. However, the federal government and the states do not embrace this philosophy.

In the United States, anti-trust laws prevent the establishment of monopolies; these laws are contained in Title 15 of United States Code (USC), which addresses Commerce and Trade. The earliest anti-trust legislation in the United States, the Sherman Antitrust Act (1890) and the Clayton Antitrust Act (1914), set out to eliminate the monopolistic practices of restraining competition through boycott, coercion, intimidation, and price-fixing agreements.

In an effort to support the intention of Congress as stated in the McCarran-Ferguson Act, the National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC) drafted model law concerning unfair trade practices in the business of insurance. The NAIC’s Unfair Trade Practices Act defines practices that represent unfair methods of competition and unfair or deceptive acts in the insurance industry. Each of the states has adopted the NAIC’s model, in either its entirety or a modified version.

Unfair Insurance Trade Practices Act
In Florida, the Unfair Insurance Trade Practices Act is spelled out in §§626.951 through 626.99 of the Florida Statutes. It applies to

All persons involved in the business of insurance, including individuals, corporations, associations, partnerships, reciprocal exchanges, interinsurers, Lloyd’s insurers, fraternal benefit societies, business trusts, and other entities; and
All insurance policies and insurance contracts, which are written agreements, contracts, and certificates that effect insurance, regardless of what they are called; this includes all riders, endorsements, provisions, clauses, and documents attached to the agreements, contracts, and certificate.
Florida Insurance Code lists and defines the unfair and deceptive trade practices that are prohibited. If any person engages in a prohibited practice, fines and penalties are severe:

Up to $5,000 for each unintentional violation, with a $20,000 aggregate applicable to insurers for all violations stemming from the same action;
Up to $40,000 for each knowing and deliberate violation, with a $200,000 aggregate applicable to insurers for all violations stemming from the same action;
For the commission of “twisting” or “churning,” which are first-degree misdemeanors:
A criminal penalty of imprisonment up to 1 year and an administrative fine up to $5,000 for each unintentional violation; or
A criminal penalty of imprisonment up to 1 year and an administrative fine up to $75,000 for each knowing and deliberate violation (this administrative fine only applies if the act involves fraudulent conduct);
For knowingly and deliberately submitting a fraudulent signature on an insurance application or insurance policy-related document, which is a third-degree felony:
A criminal penalty of imprisonment up to 5 years; or
An administrative fine up to $5,000 for each unintentional violation and $75,000 for each knowing and deliberate violation; and
Unless stated otherwise, the aggregate amount of any administrative fines stemming from the same action is $50,000 for unintentional violations and $250,000 for knowing and deliberate violations.
In addition to the prohibitions contained in Florida’s Unfair Insurance Trade Practices Act, agents should keep in mind the following requirements:

All licensees are required to make every reasonable effort to determine the age of an insurance applicant at the time the application is taken; and
If a victim of an unfair insurance trade practice is a senior citizen, a video deposition of the victim may be used for any purpose in an administrative proceeding that is conducted according to law.
Prohibited Acts and Practices - Definitions
The following acts and practices are deemed unfair methods of competition and deceptive acts; all are prohibited.

Misrepresentation and false advertising of insurance policies is the prohibited process of knowingly and deliberately making any type of estimate, illustration, presentation, comparison, or omission that misrepresents anything to do with an insurance policy. This includes the policy’s coverages, benefits, advantages, conditions, terms, provisions, and dividends. It also includes:

Making a false or misleading statement about the insurer’s financial condition;
Using a policy name or title that is misleading as to the true nature of the policy; or
Making a misrepresentation to encourage a consumer to lapse, terminate, exchange, convert, or surrender a policy or to take a loan out against a policy.
False information and advertising generally involves knowingly and deliberately publishing an advertisement, announcement, or statement to the public about any insurance matter that is untrue, deceptive, or misleading. This prohibited practice includes content placed in any of the following:

Newspapers, magazines, and other publications;
Notices, circulars, pamphlets, letters, and posters; or
Radio and television ads.
Defamation is the forbidden act of knowingly and deliberately making any type of verbal or written statement about any person that is (a) untrue, malicious, or derogatory and (b) intended to injure that person.

Entering into an agreement with the intention to create a monopoly, or restrain trade, in the insurance business by committing the acts of boycott, coercion, or intimidation is prohibited.

A person makes false statements and entries when deliberately making any false material statement in a filing with a supervisory or public official or to, or placed before, the public. In addition, a person makes prohibited false statements and entries when deliberately making a false entry of material fact pertaining to the insurance business in a book, report, or statement; this includes omitting a pertinent material fact.

Issuing, delivering, or promising agency company stock, capital stock, benefit certificates or shares, securities, or advisory board contacts that promise returns or profits as an encouragement to purchase insurance is the prohibited practice of stock operations and advisory board contracts. 

A person commits the outlawed practice of unfair discrimination when

Knowingly making or permitting unfair discrimination in premiums, policy fees, or rates charged between risks of the same rate class that have essentially the same hazard;
To increase rates, underwrite, or refuse issuance, reissuance, or renewal of a policy based upon the fact that an applicant or proposed insured submitted a claim, should have submitted a claim, or might submit a claim for abuse, protection or shelter from abuse, or assault, battery, or sexual assault by a family member; and
With respect to personal lines property or auto insurance:
For an insurer to refuse to issue, renew, or reissue a policy, or to cancel or terminate insurance, based on the lawful use, possession, or ownership of a firearm or ammunition by the applicant or insured; however, insurers may charge an actuarially sound additional premium for insuring firearms and firearms collections insured by endorsement; or
For an insurer to disclose the lawful ownership or possession of firearms of an applicant, insured, or household member of either to a third party or affiliate without complying with express and specific disclosure requirements.
The following conduct is considered making unlawful rebates:

Making any agreement pertaining to an insurance contract that is not expressly stated in the contract itself;
Paying or allowing the payment of, in any fashion, any of the following as an inducement to buy insurance if not specified in the insurance policy: premium rebate, special favor or advantage in dividends or policy benefits, or anything of value; and
Selling, giving, or allowing the sale or gift of any of the following as an inducement to buy insurance if not specified in the insurance policy: stocks, bonds, securities, dividends, or anything of value.
However, with respect to group insurance, it is NOT illegal to readjust premium rates based on losses and expenses of the contract at the end of each policy year.

It is unlawful for any person to fail to maintain a complete record of all complaints received since the last examination by the Office or Department. A complaint is any written communication that has as its primary purpose the statement of ill-treatment.

When a person makes a misrepresentation in insurance applications, he or she knowingly making a false or fraudulent statement (verbal or written) when submitting an insurance application for the purpose of obtaining a fee, commission, money, or other benefit from any insurer, agent, broker, or individual.

Twisting is the practice of knowingly making an incomplete, misleading, or fraudulent comparison, or a material and fraudulent omission of any insurance policy or insurance company for the purpose of encouraging any person to lapse, forfeit, surrender, cancel, keep, assign, borrow on, or convert any insurance policy; this includes the purchase of a new or replacement policy using these prohibited actions.

Licensees may offer advertising gifts to clients, prospective clients, and others. Advertising gifts are marketing and promotional materials such as pens and mugs. However, advertising gifts permitted are those offered by an insurer or its agent with a merchandise value up to $25 (i.e., cash gifts are not advertising gifts because they are not merchandise).

Advertising, offering, or providing free insurance is prohibited in Florida. Free insurance is insurance for which no identifiable and additional charge is made to one who purchases real property, personal property, or services. Free insurance is also insurance for which a charge is made but in an amount less than the cost of insurance on the property or services being insured.

Types of insurance that are exempt from this prohibition include blanket disability, credit life, credit disability, title, purchase agreements for cemetery lots (under stated conditions), travel insurance sold by a travel agency as part of a travel package.

It is illegal to use the word “free” or other phrases that imply insurance is being provided without a cost when advertising life or disability insurance or when offering goods, merchandise, or services for sale.

Certain practices are considered illegal dealings in premiums — excess or reduced charges for insurance:

Collecting a premium payment for insurance when knowing insurance will not be accepted or provided by the insurer;
Collecting an insurance premium payment when knowing it is the wrong premium amount, i.e., it is higher or lower than the actual premium; this prohibition does not apply to the collection of surplus lines taxes and fees or fees charged in connection with the use of a credit card;
Cancelling an existing policy during the policy term for the purpose of reissuing it for similar or identical coverage at a higher premium;
Cancelling any policy in violation of the policy’s cancellation provisions, as stated in accordance with Florida Insurance Code.
With respect to auto insurance:

Charging or requesting an additional premium under any combination of liability, PIP, medical payments, or collision coverages based solely because the insured was involved in an accident (unless the insurer has determined in good faith that the insured was at-fault); this prohibition also applies to nonrenewing a policy. Under state law, an operator was NOT at-fault if he or she was
Lawfully parked at the time of the accident;
Reimbursed by or on behalf of a person responsible for the accident or against whom a judgment was rendered;
Struck in the rear by another vehicle driving in the same direction AND the operator was not convicted of a moving traffic violation in connection with the accident;
Struck by a hit-and-run driver, so long as the accident was reported to the appropriate authorities within 24 hours of the accident;
Not convicted of a moving traffic violation in connection with the accident and the other driver was convicted of a moving traffic violation in connection with the accident;
Ruled not liable by the court;
The recipient of a traffic citation that was later dismissed; or
Otherwise not deemed at fault based on the insured’s written statement that provides the facts of the accident and those facts are not disputed by information obtained by the insurer and retained in its files and for which the insurer, in good faith, determines the insured is not at fault;
Charging or requesting an additional premium based solely on the insureds non-criminal traffic violation as defined by law unless the infraction is the second infraction within an 18-month period, the third infraction within a 36-month period, or a speeding violation at more than 15 miles per hour over the speed limit; this prohibition also applies to nonrenewing a policy;
Charging or requesting an additional premium based solely on the applicant’s handicap or physical disability so long as the handicap or disability does not substantially impair the individuals mechanically assisted driving ability; this prohibition also applies to nonrenewing a policy;
Charging an unfairly discriminatory premium based solely on the age, sex, marital status, or scholastic achievement of an individual;
Charging or requesting an additional premium for comprehensive or uninsured motorists coverage based solely on the insured’s involvement in a motor vehicle accident or conviction of a moving traffic violation; or
Cancel, nonrenew, or charge or request an additional premium based on a traffic infraction for which no points were assessed by Florida law; this prohibition does not apply to traffic infractions related to accidents if the insurer paid a claim for which the insured was deemed at-fault.
The prohibition interlocking ownership and management pertains to insurance company ownership, investment, or acquisition that substantially lessens competition in the insurance business. Specifically, this refers to one insurer buying, acquiring, or managing another insurer in violation of Insurance Code or in a fashion that may potentially harm the public (i.e., create a monopoly).

Special penalties apply to those submitting false claims or obtaining or retaining money dishonestly; in addition, this type of practice is considered a second-degree misdemeanor. If any person submits a claim for payment to an insurer while knowing it is false, secures a cash advance after making false statements, or fails to turn over to an insurer money it owes, violates this prohibition.

If a person holds securities and life insurance licenses at the same time, a proposal is required to be delivered to each prospective buyer on or before any mutual funds program is delivered. Each proposal must include a prospectus that describes the investment and provides a full illustration of any related life insurance features. The licensee must retain a copy of the prospectus for at least three years and provide the original to the consumer.

Soliciting or accepting new or renewal insurance risks by insolvent or impaired insurers is prohibited. This prohibition applies to insurance company directors and officers if they know, or should have known, the insurer was insolvent or financially impaired. Individuals violating this prohibition are guilty of a third-degree felony and subject to a criminal penalty of imprisonment up to 5 years, a fine up to $5,000, or both.

It is illegal for any person to refuse to insure any individual risk based solely on

Race, color, creed, marital status, sex, or national origin;
Age, location of residence, or the type of lawful occupation;
The refusal of the applicant or insured to place other business with the insurer;
The refusal of the applicant or insured to purchase services or products that are not insurance;
The fact that the applicant or insured is a public official; or
The fact that the applicant or insured was refused insurance previously by any insurer if the refusal to insure occurs with such frequency as to indicate a general business practice.
Insurance agents and agencies are not permitted to require the execution of powers of attorney in their favor by any applicant as a condition of purchasing insurance.

Sliding is the practice of a licensee telling an applicant that a specific type of secondary insurance must be purchased, by law, in connection with the purchase of another type of insurance coverage when the licensee’s statement is accurate. Sliding also includes stating the specific secondary coverage is included in the policy without a specific additional charge, or charging an insured for specific secondary coverage without obtaining the applicant’s informed consent, when such is not the case.

Churning is the practice of an agent or insurer cancelling and rewriting insurance with the same insurer for the purpose of earning additional premiums, fees, commissions, or other compensation. This practice involves the use of existing life insurance and annuity contract cash, loan, and dividend values, as well as policy riders and is considered an unfair method of competition AND an unfair or deceptive act or practice.

Churning is illegal when the cancel/rewrite process is undertaken

Without the agent or insurer having “a reasonable basis to believe the replacement will result in an actual and demonstrable benefit to the policyholder”;
In a fraudulent, deceptive, or misleading manner, including a deceptive omission;
Without informing the applicant the existing policy’s cash, dividend, or other policy values will be reduced, forfeited, or used to purchase the replacement policy (if applicable); or
Without informing the applicant the replacement policy will not be a paid-up policy or that additional premiums will be due (if applicable).
Insurers and agents are required to provide all applicants with a Department approved form at the time of offer that explains the extent to which policy values will be used to purchase a replacing or additional policy with the same insurance company. The form must contain the policy premium, the death benefit of the proposed replacement or new policy, and the date when the existing policy’s values will become insufficient to pay the premiums of the replacement or new policy.

Licensees are not permitted to use the name or logo of a financial institution (including banks and credit unions) during marketing and solicitation of new and existing clients without the consent of the financial institution IF the marketing and solicitation infers it is conducted on behalf of, or is endorsed by, the financial institution. Such a practice is considered deceptive use of name and is prohibited.

Licensees are not permitted the unlawful use of designations or misrepresentation of their qualifications as an agent. Specifically, licensees cannot use a designation or title in any insurance sales presentation or solicitation that falsely or fraudulently implies he or she has specialized knowledge or training or is certified or qualified to provide special financial advice to senior citizens.

If the insurance cost is specified in a “price package,” the vendor or lender must state the amounts charged for insurance, along with their classifications, separately from the property or merchandise purchased. The inclusion or exclusion of the cost of insurance from the package price of the property or merchandise cannot increase, reduce, or otherwise affect any factor related of the property/merchandise, or its financing.

The following unfair claim settlement practices apply to all lines of insurance:

Attempting to settle a claim based on a policy-related document that was altered without the insured’s knowledge or consent;
Making a material misrepresentation to an insured or claimant in order to settle a claim on less favorable terms to which he or she is entitled under the policy; or
Committing or performing with such frequency as to indicate a general business practice any of the following:
Failing to adopt and use standards to investigate claims properly;
Misrepresenting pertinent facts or policy provisions pertaining to the coverages in question;
Failing to acknowledge and respond promptly when notified of a claim;
Denying claims without conducting a reasonable investigation based upon available information;
Failing to honor or deny a claim within 30 days after proof of loss statements have been submitted; this includes failure to provide written notice a claim is being investigated;
Failing to provide prompt written explanation for the denial of a claim or the offer of a compromise settlement, based on law or the policy’s provisions;
Failing to notify the insured promptly of any addition information needed to process a claim; or
Failing to explain clearly the nature of requested information and the reasons it is necessary.
The following unfair claim settlement practices apply to property and casualty insurance:

Failing to pay personal injury protection (PIP) claims within time periods required by law; and
Failing to pay undisputed amounts of full or partial benefits owed under first-party property insurance policies within 90 days after receiving notice of a residential property insurance claim after agreeing to do so unless prevented from doing so by an act of God, the impossibility of performance, fraud on the part of the insured or claimant, lack of cooperation, or an intentional misrepresentation related to the claim.
Favored Agent or Insurer
It is illegal for any person to require, as a condition of providing any type of loan or credit, that the person borrowing money or a line of credit must purchase insurance from a particular insurer, insurance group, agent, broker, or group of agents or brokers. It is also illegal for any lender or creditor to refuse to accept an insurance policy solely based on the fact it was not obtained by an insurance affiliate or subsidiary.

Hearings and Cease and Desist Orders
If a licensee is suspected of committing a prohibited insurance trade practice, the Department will conduct a hearing to determine the validity of any allegations or charges made. If, after a hearing, the Department finds that the person charged did engage in an unfair or deceptive act or practice, transacted insurance illegally, it will issue a cease and desist order.

If the person violated Insurance Code with respect to being a favored insurer or agent or prohibited practices as defined, the Department may suspend or revoke the licensee’s certificate of authority, license, or eligibility for either if the person knew or should have known he or she violated the Insurance Code. In addition, the person may be punished according to law.

Licensees may appeal any orders of the Department or Office, including cease and desist orders and penalty orders. Penalties for violating a cease and desist order include

A monetary fine of up to $50,000 for all matters that were the subject of the hearing;
Suspension or revocation of the licensee’s certificate of authority, license, or eligibility for either; or
Any other remedies permitted by Insurance Code.
Insurance Fraud
Insurance fraud has become a problem globally, as well as here in the United States. The DFS’ Division of Investigative and Forensic Services is the Department's law enforcement arm and conducts investigations for all types of insurance fraud. For example, the Division was responsible recently for the arrest of a 31-year-old insurance agent for allegedly stealing $145,000 from a client’s annuity.

In Florida, Insurance Code specifically addresses the topic of insurance fraud for the protection of consumers and insurers. A fraudulent insurance act is committed when a person deliberately and with the intention to defraud prepares or submits a written statement related to an insurance application or claim knowing it contained materially false information; this includes concealing a material fact for the purpose of misleading another.

If the Division of Investigative and Forensic Services conducts an investigation and believes a person has engaged in, or is engaging in, a fraudulent insurance act, it may gather evidence, interview witnesses, and conduct depositions. As long as a person is not acting fraudulently or in bad faith, he or she is not subject to civil liability (i.e. granted immunity) for any relevant tort, including slander and libel, for filing reports or furnishing information to the Department or Division and cannot be sued for information submitted to or received by:

Law enforcement officials and their agents or employees;
The Department, the Division, the National Insurance Crime Bureau (NICB), the National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC), or any government officials and their agents or employees; or
Other persons.
Any and all papers, documents, reports, and evidence related to the subject of an insurance fraud investigation are confidential until the investigation is complete.

Once an investigation is complete, certain information may continue to be held confidential under certain circumstances, such as if disclosure would

Jeopardize another investigation;
Impair an insurer’s safety or soundness;
Reveal personal financial information;
Reveal the identity of a confidential source;
Defame, jeopardize the safety of, or cause undue harm to the good name or reputation of an individual; or
Reveal investigatory techniques or procedures.
The Division’s investigators have the authority to make arrests for criminal violations and are considered state law enforcement officers. They may also issue arrest and search warrants, serve subpoenas, and carry firearms (if legally licensed) while on duty.

Insurers with $10 million or more in direct written premiums are required by Florida Insurance Code to establish and maintain a fraud unit or division or contract with one or more third parties to investigate potentially fraudulent insurance claims. Insurers with less than $10 million in direct written premiums must file an anti-fraud plan with the Division no later than July 1.

Failure of an insurer to establish a fraud unit or file an anti-fraud plan as required by law will result in an administrative fine up to $2,000 per day it is not in compliance.

The Department has established an Anti-Fraud Reward Program that pays rewards up to $25,000 to those who provide information that leads to the arrest and conviction of the following violations if they are investigated by the Division:

Any willful violation of Insurance Code or an order of the Department, Office, or Commission;
Any defined unfair method of competition and unfair or deceptive act or practice;
Any fraudulent insurance act; or
Submission of a false and fraudulent insurance claim.
Only one reward may be paid for all claims arising out of the same transaction or occurrence, regardless of the number of people arrested, convicted, or submitting a claim for a reward. A single reward may be distributed to more than one person by the Department in amounts it determines. The DFS website reports that this program has awarded a total of $350,000 to 60 citizens.

Licensees who knows or believes insurance fraud is taking place, or has taken place, is required to report all pertinent information to the Division of Investigative and Forensic Services. Upon receipt of a report, the Division will review the information it contains and determine if an investigation is warranted. If conducting an investigation, the Division will report all violations of insurance law it discovers to the appropriate licensing authority and state/prosecuting agency having jurisdiction.

3. Required Premium Discounts
In Florida, property insurance carriers are required by law to provide specific premium discounts. Required premium discounts include those related to:

Policyholders who take measures to mitigate hurricane and wind damage to their buildings;
The issuance of hurricane, wind, and hail deductibles; and
Certain auto insurance endorsements.

Industry and Disciplinary Trends
1. Unauthorized Entities and Products
The sale of unauthorized insurance in Florida is illegal. Agents who sell or solicit insurance for unauthorized entities:

Violate Florida Insurance Code;
May be held liable for losses sustained by their clients that are not paid by the unauthorized entity; and
May be charged with a third degree felony that is punishable by imprisonment for up to 5 years and a monetary fine up to $5,000 for a first offense.
It is important for all insurance licensees to understand what an unauthorized insurance entity is, what types of products they sell, and what the consequences of the sale of unauthorized insurance are. Simply put, an unauthorized insurance entity does not have a license to transact the business of insurance within the jurisdiction.

Warning Signs
Many agents have a difficult time imagining how an unauthorized entity can convince a licensed professional it is authorized to transact insurance. However, many marketing representatives appear legitimate and are able to convince licensees and consumers alike that their products are superior to the competition’s products and that they are less expensive. Sales materials prepared by unauthorized entities often appear impressive, being accompanied by letters from insurance regulators and other organizations that make them appear legitimate.

Warning signs that a company is an unauthorized entity include

The premium is at least 25% lower than its competitors’ premiums AND the company claims its product is more comprehensive than other products. This is a difficult temptation to resist, especially for prospective insureds with few financial resources.
The insurer has few, if any, underwriting guidelines or its only eligibility requirement is for applicants to join a trade association, union, or affinity group to earn eligibility for coverage.
The insurer claims to be exempt from state insurance regulation because it is regulated under the Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA) (i.e., the federal government). Although some plans may actually be regulated by ERISA, this claim is the number one indicator of unauthorized entities because most agents are not familiar with federal insurance regulations and dismiss any irregularities as being related to the difference between state and federal insurance regulations.
The company’s advertising and sales materials refer to benefits rather than insurance and refer to the policy as a health benefit plan instead. In some cases, company representatives and agents actually ask the applicant not to use the term insurance when discussing the plan.
The insurer claims to be a Multiple Employer Welfare Arrangement (MEWA), which is an entity that, according to the Department of Labor’s Employee Benefits Security Administration (EBSA) “provides health and welfare benefits to employees of two or more unrelated employers that are not parties to a bona fide collective bargaining agreement.) While many MEWAs are formed legally, many others are not. Because MEWAs often use the employer’s premium payments to pay benefits directly to employees rather than to buy insurance, they are very attractive products for unauthorized entities to sell.
The company will offer investments that are, in fact, unregistered securities (i.e., communications equipment companies and real estate and land development opportunities).
The company will claim to be a self-funded health plan, which is not the same thing as a fully insured employee benefit plan. A self-funded health plan is insurance that is paid fully by the employer, which, in turn, pays benefits directly to employees. Most self-funded plans are not regulated by the state but are regulated by ERISA.
The company will sell a union plan, or collective bargaining arrangement. These plans are legal contracts between a labor union and an employer and, because they are not MEWAs, are subject to state insurance regulation. However, many unauthorized entities claim to be collective bargaining agreements or arrangements to avoid ERISA regulations.
Professional employer organizations (PEOs), which used to be referred to as employee leasing companies, that sponsor health plans are not subject to ERISA regulations because they do not involve an employer/employee relationship. The individuals they hire out are not employees of the PEO; they are employees of the companies to whom the PEO hire them out. Because of the many regulatory requirements of PEOs that sponsor health plans, unauthorized entities favor this type of organization because businesses find their complexity difficult to follow and they often simply trust the “agent” selling them.
How to Determine if a Company is Authorized
The Florida DFS holds agents responsible for exhibiting due diligence and confirming the insurance companies they represent are authorized to transact insurance in this state and to verify that an investment is registered. The DFS assists licensees in their efforts to verify that all insurers they represent are authorized to transact insurance in this state.

The first action an agent should take before representing any insurance company is to visit the OIR website at http://www.floir.com/CompanySearch/ to verify whether it is authorized to do business in Florida. Because many insurance companies share similar names, agents should be sure to obtain the full legal name of the insurer. If the insurer’s name is returned after completing a search, it has authority to transact insurance in Florida if its Authorization Status is active and any of the following appear in its Authorization Type:

Certificate of Authority;
Information Only;
Letter of Approval;
Letter of Eligibility;
Letter of Registration;
License;
Provisional Certificate of Authority; or
Residual Market.
If the Authorization Status is active and the Authorization Type is permit, the insurer is NOT yet authorized to transact insurance in Florida because it has only begun the authorization process.

If the insurance company is not listed on the website or if it has an Authorization Status that is not “active” or an Authorization Type not listed above, AGENTS SHOULD ASSUME THE ENTITY IS UNAUTHORIZED AND NOT PLACE BUSINESS WITH THAT INSURER.
If an insurance company is a surplus lines insurer, agents can verify its authority by visiting the website of the National Association of Professional Surplus Lines Offices, Ltd. (NAPSLO) to search for a member company at https://www.napslo.org/wcm/Members/Find_A_NAPSLO_Member/wcm/_iCore/Contacts/Members.aspx?hkey=37a0f747-50e3-4168-ada8-ff372711c577.

The Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA) website contains a page “Ask and Check” that allows consumers and agents to verify if the seller of an investment is licensed to sell it and if an investment is registered with the Securities Exchange Commission (SEC). The website can be found at http://www.finra.org/investors/ask-and-check.

2. Recent Enforcement Actions
Third Degree Felony: License Revoked
In October 2016, a life/variable producer had his agent license revoked, and is barred from reapplying for licensure for 7 years after a conviction for cocaine possession. Licensing rules require that a producer convicted of a crime (in this case, a third-degree felony) must immediately report the conviction to the Florida regulator. This individual self-reported the conviction and after an administrative hearing, had his license revoked.

FINRA Violation: License Revoked
A Florida agent licensed for life, variable annuity, health, and general lines had her license revoked in 2016 after the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA) fined her more than $50,000 and suspended her FINRA registration for 18 months for violating Section 5 of the Securities Act of 1933 (unregistered distribution of securities).

The agent failed to notify or obtain permission from her member firms after earning private sales commissions of nearly $40,000. She advised multiple customers to purchase unregistered securities without conduct adequate due diligence or suitability evaluations. Under Florida statutes, it is a violation for an "agent to have been the subject of or to have had a license, permit, appointment, registration, or other authority to conduct business subject to any decision, finding, injunction, suspension, prohibition, revocation, denial, judgment, final agency action, or administrative order by any court of competent jurisdiction, administrative law proceeding, state agency, federal agency, national securities, commodities, or option exchange, or national securities, commodities, or option association involving a violation of any federal or state securities or commodities law or any rule or regulation adopted thereunder, or a violation of any rule or regulation of any national securities, commodities, or options exchange or national securities, commodities, or options association." The agent is permitted to apply for reinstatement of her license and appointments in 2 years when the suspension is over.

False Application: License Revoked
In 2016, a Clearwater agent was found to have submitted seven false and fraudulent life insurance applications for the sole purpose of receiving commissions. An audit undertaken by the issuing insurer determined that the applications were false and that none of the applicants actually existed or desired to purchase the insurance, and premiums were never received. Because the applications were false and material misstatements of fact, the agent was charged with violating Florida Insurance Code prohibiting fraudulent or dishonest practices in the conduct of business under the license. The agent's license was revoked and she is ineligible to reapply for 2 years.

Fraudulent Placement: License Revoked
In May 2016 a Melbourne agent licensed for life, health and variable insurance as well as as a customer service representative was found to have fraudulently represented himself as a general lines agent for the purpose of fraudulently transacting homeowners insurance. The investigation found that he collected premiums without completing applications, provided false evidence of coverage, and never placed the coverage with an insurer and allowed existing coverage to lapse. These activities are considered unfair or deceptive acts/practices under Florida law, engaging in fraudulent or dishonest practices in the conduct of business under the license or appointment, and misappropriating, converting, or unlawfully withholding moneys belonging to insurers or insureds received in conduct of business under the license. The agent's license was revoked and other disciplinary penalties are underway.

Transacting without a License: Suspension
In October, 2016, the Department alleged that an individual licensed as a life, health and variable annuity agent had solicited insurance business without possessing the proper licensure in violation of section 626.112.(2), Florida Statutes. Without admitting guilt, the agent agreed via a consent order to a fine of $2,500 and a license suspension for 3 months.

3. Important Terminology
Authorized or Unauthorized Insurer
In Florida, an authorized insurer is one that has been granted a certificate of authority to transact insurance in this state. An unauthorized insurer does not have a certificate of authority in Florida.

Certificate of Authority
A certificate of authority is a written agreement between an insurance company and a state or other jurisdiction that gives the insurance company the authority to transact insurance within that state or jurisdiction. The certificate of authority lists the lines of insurance the insurance company is authorized to transact.

Base Flood
A based flood (also referred to as a 100-year flood) is the flood that has a 1% chance of being equaled or exceeded in any given year.

Base Flood Elevation (BFE)
The base flood elevation is the elevation shown on a flood insurance rate map (FIRM) for special flood hazard areas that indicates the water surface elevation resulting from a base flood.

National Flood Insurance Program
The National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP) is a federal program that enables property owners in participating communities to purchase flood insurance. Flood insurance provided by the NFIP is designed as an alternative to disaster assistance.

Special Flood Hazard Area (SFHA)
A special flood hazard area (SFHA) is an area identified by FEMA as having a high-risk of flood and where flood insurance is mandatory for property secured by a federally regulated or insured lender. SFHAs are indicated in flood insurance rate maps as A and V flood zones.

Grandfather Rule
Under the NFIP, grandfathering is an exemption based on circumstances that existed previously and allows eligible buildings to receive subsidized flood insurance premium rates if they are remapped into special flood hazard areas (SFHAs) or if their base flood elevations are higher after remapping.

Best Interest Contract Exemption
Part of the DOL Conflict of Interest (Fiduciary) Rule. Requires advisors who limit recommendations to proprietary products to clearly notify the client in writing that the firm offers proprietary products or receives third-party payments for the recommended investment product. The client must also be informed of limitations the advisor may have to only recommend a specific group of products.

Fiduciary Standard
Being a fiduciary means that financial advisors will have to act in their clients' best interests regarding retirement accounts such as IRAs and 401(k) plans.

Suitability Standard
Advisers need to ensure that the financial product is suitable for the client's situation.

Insurance Terms and Related Concepts
Risk is uncertainty of loss.
Insurance is a transfer of risk from the insured to the insurer.
Pure risk means there is no chance of gain. Pure risk is insurable.
Speculative risk means there is a chance of a loss or a gain. Speculative risks are not insurable.
A hazard is something that increases the risk.
The principle of indemnity governs property and casualty policies. It states that the purpose of the policy is to restore the insured financially to where they were prior to their loss.
Insurable interest must exist on a casualty policy at time of loss in order for the policy to provide coverage.
The law of large numbers is used to predict the likelihood of loss.
Actual cash value is replacement cost minus depreciation.
Negligence is a tort, or a civil wrong; it is grounds for a lawsuit.
Negligence is the failure to act as a reasonable person would in the same set of circumstances.
An occurrence happens over a period of time.
A binder may be oral or written.
A binder provides coverage until the policy is issued.
A binder includes all coverages provided by the policy.
A warranty is a literal truth.
A representation is a substantial truth. In insurance, statements of the applicant/policyowner are representations – true to the best of their knowledge.
Concealment is an omission of a material fact.
The insurer has the right to sue a negligent third party for damages paid to an insured under the concept of subrogation.

Provisions and Contract Law
Policy Structure:
The four parts of a policy may be remembered by the acronym D-I-C-E (declarations, insuring agreement, conditions, and exclusions).
The declarations list the named insured, policy limits, and premium and policy period.
The limits of liability are found on the declaration page of the policy.
The insuring agreement describes the coverages provided.
The conditions list the obligations of both parties, the insurer and the insured.
The exclusions list the perils that are not covered.
Provisions and Clauses:
If the insurer and insured disagree that the liability policy does or does not provide coverage, the claim will go to arbitration.
In arbitration there are three arbitrators.
The cancellation provisions are found in the conditions section of the policy.
The insured must promptly tell the insurer about a claim.
The other insurance clause is also known as the pro-rata liability clause.
Pro-rata does not mean equal, it is proportionate.
Federal Regulations:
The Fair Credit Reporting Act protects consumers against the circulation of inaccurate or obsolete personal or financial information.
The Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act requires that a customer be given out a privacy notice at the time the customer relationship is initially established and thereafter annually.
 The Terrorism Risk Insurance Act (TRIA) applies to commercial policies only.

Dwelling Policy
The main difference between the various dwelling policy (DP) forms is the property perils insured against.
DP policies do not cover personal liability, although it can be added by adding an endorsement known as a Personal Liability Supplement for an additional premium charge.
DP policies contain general exclusions for damage due to war, nuclear hazard, and flood but not wind.
On a dwelling policy, other structures coverage will apply to a structure rented out as a private garage.
DP policies do not cover breakage of glass after 60 days of vacancy.
DP policies do not cover freezing of plumbing unless the heat was left on.
The land on which the insured dwelling sits is not insurable.
Inflation guard, also known as the automatic increase endorsement, must be added to a DP policy by endorsement.
A loss from rain or dust would only be covered if an opening in the dwelling roof or walls was first created by wind or another covered cause of loss.
When a dwelling is covered by more than one policy, losses are shared pro-rata under the other insurance clause. This may also be referred to as the pro-rata liability clause.
The Basic dwelling form DP-1 is a named or specified peril policy.
The DP-1 basic form does not provide additional living expense under coverage D; only fair rental value is provided.
The Extended Coverage Endorsement is added to the Standard Fire Policy to create the DP-1.
A DP-2 Broad Form policy is named perils on both the dwelling and the contents.
On the dwelling broad form DP-2 building structures (Coverages A and B) are written with an 80% coinsurance requirement.
On a DP-2 broad form, Coverage B (other structures) is in addition to other coverage limits.
The DP-3 policy will provide the same coverage as the DP-2 (contents broad) for personal property coverage, should coverage for contents be declared.
Although the DP-1 Basic Form does not provide coverage for trees, shrubs, plants and lawns, both the DP-2 and DP-3 do.
When a dwelling policy is referred to as DP-2 ('02), it is referring to the Dwelling Property Broad Form policy. The ('02) means it is the ISO policy form that was introduced in 2002.

Homeowners Policy
All HO policies are package policies combining property and liability coverages.
The most a policy will pay under the liability section is known as the limit of liability.
The definition of an insured includes residents of a household who are relatives, or any other person under age 21 who is in the insured's care.
All HO policies exclude coverage for flood, landslides or mudslides.
The homeowners policy does not cover theft of animals, birds or fish.
Personal injury liability for false arrest, libel, slander, defamation, and invasion of privacy is not automatically covered on an HO, but can be added by endorsement for an additional premium.
The land on which a house sits is not insurable on HO policies.
Section II (liability) provides additional coverage for damage to the property of others up to $1,000 per occurrence.
An HO policy will not cover the property of a boarder/renter, but will cover the property of a guest or residence employee.
An HO policy will provide coverage for contents anywhere in the world, including theft.
An HO policy written on a dwelling under the course of construction will not cover theft.
Medical coverage will cover charges for medical, surgical, x-ray, dental, ambulance, hospital, nursing, prosthetic devices and funeral services.
Medical payments never apply to regular members of the household.
The bankruptcy of an insured does not relieve the insurer of their obligations under the policy.
Claims resulting from the enforcement of an ordinance or law are not covered by most property policies, although limited coverage is provided as additional coverage.
The insurer's duty to defend a lawsuit is stated in the insuring agreement.
Additional coverages (such as for trees, shrubs and plants) are in addition to limits.
HO liability covers bodily injury to a third party.
If the insurer cancels an HO policy, they must send advance written notice to both the mortgage company and the named insured.
An HO policy will not pay the cost of defense on an excluded claim.
An HO policy covers contents in full while moving, for up to 30 days.
HO Coverage C will not cover property of a roomer, boarder or other tenant unless related to the insured.
Damage due to rain is not covered on a property policy unless the roof or wall was first damaged by wind or hail, allowing the rain to enter.
Property policies do not cover damage to motorized vehicles, other than those used to maintain the premises (e.g. riding lawn mowers).
Personal liability and medical coverage cover the insured's activities both on and off the premises.
Loss of use covers only additional living expenses.
The insurer's duty to defend a lawsuit ends when the amount paid out for damages equals the limit of liability.
A person who is hired to maintain a premises is referred to as a residence employee.
At the insured's option, recovered property will be returned to the insured or retained by the insurer. If returned, the loss payment must be adjusted.
After a loss, if the cost of reconstructing a home exceeds its market value, the insurer will consider it to be a constructive total loss.
HO-2 is named peril on both the dwelling and contents.
HO-3 is all-risk on a dwelling, but named peril on its contents.
In the HO-3 special form policy, theft of personal property of a resident employee is covered.
HO-4 are property policies issued to tenants to cover contents extend coverage to losses caused by a covered peril to improvements, alterations and additions made to the described location at the tenant's expense.
On HO-6 policy, contents coverage is named perils.
HO-6 (unit-owners form) does not cover common area buildings.
HO-8 was created specifically for older homes.

Personal Auto
Liability:
Liability covers BI and PD to others for which an insured is proven to be negligent.
The Auto Assigned Risk Plan provides a method for those who have been rejected in the normal market to obtain coverage.
All authorized insurers selling auto insurance must participate in the Auto Assigned Risk Plan.
Supplementary payments under a PAP do not cover the insured's loss of earnings except when the insured is attending a hearing or trial at the insurer's request. The insured's injuries are not covered.
The personal auto coverage form will provide coverage for radios and tape decks if they are permanently installed in the dash.
The medical payment section of the personal automobile policy pays necessary medical and funeral expenses caused by an accident and sustained by an insured.
The medical payments coverage found in the personal automobile policy will not pay for lost wages.
Auto medical on a PAP protects the insured and passengers in the car. It is an optional coverage. It is not a supplementary payment, and it is no-fault.
On a PAP, an at-fault driver's injuries would be covered by medical.
Physical Damage:
Coverage D on a PAP is called coverage for damage to an insured's car and is optional. It is divided into collision and other than collision.
Other than collision coverage is also known as comprehensive coverage.
Coverage D is written on an ACV basis and has a deductible. Collision coverage on the PAP covers colliding with another object, rollover and upset. Everything else is covered by other than collision coverage.
Hitting a pole with an insured automobile would be an example of a collision.
Hitting a deer is an example of other than collision.
If a bird were to hit the insured's windshield, the windshield is covered under other than collision on a PAP.
Towing and labor is an optional coverage on the PAP and costs extra.
The optional coverage limit for towing and labor pays on a per event/occurrence basis.
In an accident, the owner's PAP is always the primary policy; the driver's PAP, if different, is always the excess policy.
Uninsured Motorists:
Insureds purchase uninsured motorist coverage because of their concern of being in an auto accident with someone who has no insurance and is at-fault.
Included in the definition of an uninsured motorist is a hit-and-run driver, one whose insurer has gone bankrupt, and one who does not carry the state minimum limits.
If an individual is concerned about being in an auto accident with someone who has inadequate limits of liability and who is at-fault, they would purchase underinsured motorist coverage.
Exclusions:
A PAP does not provide coverage in Mexico.
A PAP does not cover an insured's property in transit.
Auto medical covers the insured and any passengers, but not injured pedestrians.
A PAP will cover small pick-up trucks, even if they are used for farming or ranching, but will not cover motorcycles, dump trucks or farm implements driven on the highway.
On the PAP, exclusions under other than collision include wear and tear, freezing and mechanical breakdown.
The PAP does not cover autos used as taxis or livery, but carpools are covered.

Other Property and Liability Coverages
A mobile home endorsement modifies an HO policy to cover a mobile home and other structures while located on the mobile home resident's owned or leased land.
A mobile home policy pays up to $500 if moved by the insured to a safe area, to protect it from losses caused by a covered peril.
Watercraft coverage pays for bodily injury or property damage resulting from the use of any watercraft, outboard motors, or watercraft trailers.
Medical payments to others under a watercraft policy covers expenses arising from medical and funeral services sustained by an insured, as long as the services rendered occur within 3 years of the accident date.
Windstorm coverage applies to losses arising from high risk areas often require a separate windstorm policy.
For states in which private insurers do not offer windstorm policies, a state-sponsored insurance pool would provide coverage.
For standard policy forms which exclude coverage for earthquake damage, coverage for said peril may be added by endorsement.
Inland marine coverage can be written on almost any type of property that is portable, and in transit over land or in the air.
Personal inland marine policies are often called floaters. 
The scheduled personal property endorsement is used to insure personal property with high values such as furs, antiques, and jewelry.
Inland Marine:
A list of risks eligible for inland marine insurance published by the National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC) is known as the Nationwide Definition.
On equipment breakdown insurance, the insurer may inspect the insured's equipment, but they are not required to.
The scheduled personal property endorsement is used to insure personal property with high values such as furs, antiques, and jewelry.
To properly insure computer equipment, an individual would buy a data processing floater.
A fine arts floater will provide automatic coverage for newly acquired fine art for 90 days.
A scheduled personal property floater provides coverage on an ACV basis.
In case of a loss to a pair or set, the insurer may elect to repair or replace the set to its value before the loss, or pay the difference in value before and after the loss. To calculate the difference, the insurer would subtract the value of remaining from the value of the full set.
National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP):
The FIA (Federal Insurance Administration) sets flood insurance rates. To qualify for NFIP, a community must cooperate with the FIA.
Flood is defined as the temporary inundation of normally dry land.
Flood insurance will not cover wharves, piers or docks.
NFIP flood insurance does not cover sewer backup or seepage through walls.
Flood insurance is sold by the government and by participating private insurers, but claims are paid by the federal government.
The maximum coverage permitted under the regular NFIP program is $250,000 for a single-family home.
To be eligible for federal flood insurance, the community must participate in the NFIP.
Umbrella and Excess Liability:
A personal umbrella liability policy will pay on an excess basis, only after a primary policy has already paid.
An excess limits policy, such as an umbrella, is one written over and above the primary liability policy's limits of insurance.
Umbrella policies contain a retention requirement that is like a deductible and must be paid by the insured in the event of a claim.
Umbrella policies are not written on standardized industry forms.
On a personal umbrella policy, the retained limit is defined as the policy limits of the primary policies.

Abandonment
The abdication of insured property into the hands of another, or into the possession of no one in particular.
Absolute Liability
A type of liability that occurs due to extremely dangerous operations, such as the use of explosives or working at extreme heights.
Accident
An unplanned, unforeseen event which occurs suddenly and at a specific place.
Actual Cash Value (ACV)
The required amount to pay damages or for property loss, which is calculated based on the property's current replacement value minus depreciation.
Additional Coverage
A provision in an insurance policy that allows for more coverage for specific loss expense without increase in premium.
Additional Insureds
Individuals or businesses that are not named as insured on the declaration page, but are protected by the policy, usually in regard to a specific interest.
Adhesion
A contract offered on a "take-it-or-leave-it" basis by an insurer, in which the insured's only option is to accept or reject the contract. Any ambiguities in the contract will be settled in favor of the insured.
Admitted Insurer
An insurance company authorized and licensed to transact business in a particular state.
Adverse Selection
The tendency of risks with higher probability of loss to purchase and maintain insurance more often than the risks who present lower probability.
Agent
An individual who is licensed to sell, negotiate, or effect insurance contracts on behalf of an insurer.
Aggregate Limit
The maximum limit of coverage available under a liability policy during a policy year regardless of the number of claims that may be made or the number of accidents that may occur.
Agreed Value
A property policy with a provision agreed upon by the insurer and insured as to the amount of insurance that represents a fair valuation for the property at the time the insurance is written.
Aleatory
A contract in which the participating parties agree to exchange unequal amounts. Insurance contracts are aleatory in that the amount the insured will pay in premiums is unequal to the amount the insurer will pay in the event of a loss.
Alien Insurer
An insurance company that is incorporated outside the United States.
Apparent Authority
The appearance or the assumption of authority based on the actions, words, or deeds of the principal or because of circumstances the principal created.
Appraisal
An assessment of property to determine either the correct amount of insurance to be written or the amount of loss to be paid.
Arbitration
Method of claim settlement used when the insured and insurer cannot agree upon the amount of the loss.
Assignment
The transfer of a legal right or interest in an insurance policy. In property and casualty insurance, assignments of policies are usually valid only with the prior written consent of the insurer.
Authorized Insurer
An insurance company that has qualified and received a Certificate of Authority from the Department of Insurance to transact insurance in the state.
Auto
A land motor vehicle, trailer or semi-trailer designed for use on public roads, including attached machinery or equipment; auto does not include mobile equipment.
Avoidance
A method of dealing with risk by deliberately keeping away from it (e.g., if a person wanted to avoid the risk of dying in an airplane crash, they might choose never to fly in a plane).
Bailee
A person or entity that has possession of personal property entrusted to them by the owner. For example, a television repair person that has possession of a customer's television would be a bailee.
Beneficiary
The person who receives the proceeds from the insurance policy.
Binder
A temporary contract that puts an insurance policy into force before the premium has been paid.
Blanket Bond
A type of bond that covers losses caused by dishonest employees.
Blanket Insurance
A single property insurance policy that provides coverage for multiple classes of property at one location, or provides coverage for one or more classes of property at multiple locations.
Bodily Injury Liability
Legal liability arising from death or physical trauma to a person as a result of a negligent or purposeful act and omissions by an insured.
Boycott
An unfair trade practice in which one person refuses to do business with another until they agree to certain conditions.
Builder's Risk Coverage Form
A commercial property form that covers buildings under construction.
Building and Personal Property Coverage Form
A commercial property form that covers buildings, and/or their contents.
Burglary
The forced entry into another's premises with felonious intent.
Cancellation
The termination of an in-force insurance policy by either the insured or the insurer prior to the expiration date shown in the policy.
Casualty Insurance
A type of insurance that covers losses caused by injury to persons or damage to the property of others.
Cease and Desist Order
A demand of a person to stop committing an action that is in violation of a provision.
Certificate of Authority
A document that authorizes a company to start conducting business and specifies the kind(s) of insurance a company can transact. It is illegal for an insurance company to transact insurance without this certificate.
Certificate of Insurance
A legal document that indicates that an insurance policy has been issued, and that states both the amounts and types of insurance provided.
Claim
A demand made by the insured to cover a loss protected by the insurance policy.
Class Rating
The practice of computing a price per unit of insurance that applies to all applicants possessing a given set of characteristics.
Coercion
An unfair trade practice in which an insurer uses physical or mental force to persuade an applicant to buy insurance.
Coinsurance
An agreement between an insurer and insured in which both parties are expected to pay a certain portion of the potential loss and other expenses.
Combined Single
A single dollar limit of liability applying to the total of damages for bodily injury and property damage combined, resulting from one accident or occurrence.
Commercial Lines
Type of insurance that pertains to business, mercantile or manufacturing establishments.
Commissioner (Superintendent, Director)
The chief executive and administrative officer of a state insurance department.
Common Law
An unwritten body of law based on past judicial decisions as well as usages and customs.
Complaint
A written statement of a liability claim given by the claimant; a reason for a lawsuit.
Components
Factors that determine rates, including loss reserves, loss adjusting expenses, operating expenses and profits.
Comprehensive Coverage
Also known as Other Than Collision coverage, it covers losses by fire, theft, vandalism, falling objects, etc.
Concealment
The withholding of known facts which, if material, can void a contract.
Concurrent causation
Multiple events leading to one loss.
Conditional Contract
A type of an agreement in which both parties must perform certain duties and follow rules of conduct to make the contract enforceable.
Conditions
The section of an insurance policy that indicates the general rules or procedures that the insurer and insured agree to follow under the terms of the policy.
Consideration
The binding force in a contract that requires something of value to be exchanged for the transfer of risk. The consideration on the part of the insured is the representations made in the application and the payment of premium; the consideration on the part of the insurer is the promise to pay in the event of loss.
Consultant
A person who, for a fee, offers any advice, counsel, opinion, or service regarding the benefits, advantages, or disadvantages promised under a policy of insurance.
Consumer Reports
Written and /or oral statements regarding a consumer's credit, character, reputation, or habits collected by a reporting agency from employment records, credit reports, and other public sources.
Contract
An agreement between two or more parties enforceable by law.
Controlled Business
An entity that obtains and possesses a license solely for the purpose of writing business on the owner, immediate family, relatives, employer and employees.
Declarations
The section of an insurance policy containing the basic underwriting information, such as the insured's name, address, amount of coverage and premiums, and a description of insured locations, as well as any supplemental representations by the insured.
Deductible
The portion of the loss that is to be paid by the insured before any claim benefits may be paid by the insurer.
Defamation
An unfair trade practice in which one agent or insurer makes an injurious statement about another with the intent of harming the person’s or company’s reputation.
Deposit Premium Audit
A condition that allows the insurer to audit the insured's books or records at the end of the policy term to make sure adequate premium has been collected for the exposure.
Depreciation
The lessening of value of real and personal property due to age and wear and tear.
Direct Losses
Physical damage to buildings and/or personal property as a result of direct consequence of a particular peril.
Director (Commissioner, Superintendent)
The head of the state department of insurance.
Disability
A physical or mental impairment, either congenital or resulting from an injury or sickness.
Disclosure
An act of identifying the name of the producer, representative or firm, limited insurance representative, or temporary insurance producer on any policy solicitation.
Domestic Insurer
An insurance company that is incorporated in the state.
Domicile of Insurer
Insurer's location of incorporation and the legal ability to write business in a state.
Economic Loss
The estimated total cost (both insured and uninsured) of an accident.
Endorsement
A printed addendum to a contract that is used to change the policy's original terms, conditions, or coverages.
Estoppel
A legal impediment to denying a fact or restoring a right that has been previously waived.
Excess Policy
A policy that only pays for loss after the primary policy has paid its limit.
Exclusions
Causes of loss, exposures, conditions, etc. listed in the policy for which the benefits will not be paid.
Exclusive or Captive Agent
An agent who represents only one company and is compensated by commissions.
Experience Rating
Method of determining the premium based on the insured's own past loss experience.
Exposure
A unit of measure used to determine rates charged for insurance coverage.
Express Authority
The authority granted to an agent by means of the agent's written contract.
Extensions of Coverage
A provision in some property policies which allows the extension of a major coverage to certain types of loss to property not specifically insured.
FAIR Plan
Fair Access to Insurance Requirements plan is a state-run program that makes insurance obtainable to those in high risk areas who have been unable to acquire insurance through other channels.
Fiduciary
An agent/broker who handles insurer's funds in a trust capacity.
First Named Insured
The individual whose name appears first on the policy's declaration
Flood
A general and temporary condition of partial or complete inundation of normally dry land areas from overflow of inland or tidal waters or from the unusual and rapid accumulation or runoff of surface waters from any source.
Foreign Insurer
An insurance company that is incorporated in another state.
Fraternal Benefit Society
A life or health insurance company formed to provide insurance for members of an affiliated lodge, religious, or fraternal organization with a representative form of government.
Fraud
Intentional misrepresentation or deceit with the intent to induce a person to part with something of value.
Functional Replacement Cost
The cost to replace damaged property with less expensive and more modern construction or equipment.
Gross Negligence
Reckless behavior that shows disregard for the safety or lives of others.
Hazard
A circumstance that increases the likelihood of a loss.
Hazard, Moral
The effect of a person’s reputation, character, or living habits on their insurability.
Hazard, Morale
The effect a person’s indifference concerning loss has on the risk to be insured.
Hazard, Physical
A type of hazard that arises from the physical characteristics of an individual, such as a physical disability due to either current circumstance or a condition present at birth.
Implied Authority
Authority that is not expressed or written into the contract, but which the agent is assumed to have in order to transact the business of insurance for the principal.
Indemnity
Compensation to the insured that restores them to the same financial position that they enjoyed prior to the loss.
Independent Agents
Agents that sell the insurance products of several companies and work for themselves or other agents.
Indirect Losses
Losses resulting from a peril, but not directly caused by it. Indirect losses may include business disruption, rent insurance, extra expenses, and other consequences that occur over time.
Inflation Guard
A coverage extension that automatically increases amounts of insurance on buildings by an agreed upon percentage annually.
Insurable Interest
Any interest an insured may have in property that is the subject of insurance, so that damage or destruction of that property would cause the insured financial loss.
Insurance
The transfer of the possibility of a loss (risk) to an insurance company, which in turn spreads the costs of unexpected losses to many individuals.
Insurance Policy
A contract between an insured and an insurance company which agrees to pay the insured for loss caused by specific events.
Insured
The person or organization that is protected by insurance; the party to be indemnified.
Insured Contract
A definition on liability forms that describes the types of contracts in which liability is assumed by the insured and included for coverage in the policy. Examples of insured contracts are leases of premises, elevator maintenance agreements, easement agreements, and other agreements related to the insured's business.
Insurer
An entity that indemnifies against losses, provides benefits, or renders services (also known as the "company" or "insurance company").
Insuring Agreement
The section of an insurance policy containing the insurer's promise to pay, the description of coverage provided and perils insured against.
Intentional Tort
Any deliberate act that causes harm to another person.
Interline Endorsement
A written amendment designed to eliminate redundancy and minimize the number of endorsements in the policy.
Judgment Rating
An approach used when credible statistics are lacking or when the exposure units are so varied that it is impossible to construct a class.
Law of Large Numbers
A principle stating that the larger the number of similar exposure units considered, the more closely the losses reported will equal the underlying probability of loss.
Legal Liability
A liability under the law that occurs when a person is responsible for injuries or damages to another due to negligence.
Liability
Responsibility under the law.
Liberalization
A property insurance clause that extends broader legislated or regulated coverage to current policies, as long as it does not result in a higher premium.
Lien
A charge, security or encumbrance on property.
Limit of Liability
The maximum amount for which an insurer is liable.
Lloyd's Associations
Organizations that provide support facilities for underwriters or groups of individuals that accept insurance risk.
Loss
The reduction, decrease, or disappearance of value of the person or property insured in a policy, by a peril insured against.
Loss Payable Clause
A provision in property insurance that is used to cover the interest of a secured lender in personal property.
Loss Ratio
A calculation used by insurance companies to relate income from loss expenses: loss ratio = (incurred losses + loss adjusting expense) / earned premium.
Loss Valuation
A factor in determining the premium charged and the amount of insurance required.
Market Value
A seldom used method of valuing a loss based upon the amount a willing buyer would pay to a willing seller for the property prior to the loss.
Misrepresentation
A false statement or lie that can render the contract void.
Monoline Policy
A policy written separately as a single coverage.
Mutual Assessment Insurer
A mutual insurance company with the right to assess policyholder's additional amounts of premium to meet operational needs.
Mutual Companies
Insurance organizations that have no capital stock, but are owned by the policyholders.
Mysterious Disappearance
A disappearance of property that cannot be explained as to the location, time or the manner of property loss.
Named Insured
The individual(s) whose name appears on the policy's declaration.
Named Peril
The cause of loss specifically covered by the insurance policy. No coverage is provided for unlisted perils.
Negligence
The failure to use the care that a reasonable, prudent person would under the same or similar circumstances.
No Benefit to the Bailee
A provision that excludes any assignment or granting of any policy provision to any person or organization holding, storing, repairing, or moving insured property for a fee.
Nonadmitted Insurer
An insurance company that has not applied, or has applied and been denied a Certificate of Authority and may not transact insurance.
Nonconcurrency
A situation in which other insurance is written on the same risk, but not on the same coverage basis.
Nonrenewal
A termination of a policy by an insurer on the anniversary or renewal date.
Notice of Claim
A provision that spells out an insured’s duty to provide the insurer with reasonable notice in the event of a loss.
Occurrence
A broader definition of loss, which differs from accident in that it includes losses caused by continuous or repeated exposure to conditions resulting in injury to persons or damage to property that is neither intended nor expected.
Open Peril
Term used in property insurance to describe the breadth of coverage provided under an insurance policy form that insures against "any risk of loss" that is not specifically excluded.
Pair and Set Clause
A clause included in many property and inland marine policies, which provides that the insurer is not obligated to pay for the total value of a set of items if only one item has been lost, damaged or destroyed.
Partnership
A legal entity in which 2 or more persons agree to share the profits and losses of the business.
Passive
A description of an anti-theft device or system for autos which is activated automatically when the driver turns the ignition key to the off position and the key is removed.
Peril
The cause of a possible loss.
Personal Injury Liability
Legal responsibility for an injury to the character of another person caused by libel, slander, false arrest, invasion of privacy and other acts.
Personal Lines
Insurance – Type of coverage available to individuals and families for non-business risks.
Policy Limits
The maximum amount an insured may collect, or for which an insured is protected under the terms of the policy.
Policy Period
A period of time a policy is in effect (also known as Policy Term).
Policyholder
The person in possession of an insurance policy; may or may not be the policyowner and/or insured.
Policyowner
The person who is entitled to exercise the rights and privileges in the policy. This person may or may not be the insured.
Premium
A periodic payment to the insurance company to keep the policy in force.
Primary Policy
A basic, fundamental insurance policy which pays first with respect to other outstanding policies.
Pro Rata
Proportional distribution of shares of the loss for each insurance policy written on a piece of property.
Producer
A person who acts on the behalf of the insurer to sell, negotiate, or effect insurance contracts; also known as an agent.
Proof of Loss
A sworn statement that must usually be furnished by the insured to an insurer before any loss under a policy can be paid.
Property Damage Liability
Legal liability arising from physical damage to tangible property of others caused by the negligence of an insured.
Proximate Cause
An act or event that is the immediate or actual cause of a loss.
Pure Risk
Situations that can only result in a loss or no change. Pure risk is the only type of risk insurance companies are willing to accept.
Rebating
Any inducement offered in the sale of insurance products that is not specified in the policy.
Reciprocal
Insurance resulting from an interchange of reciprocal agreements of indemnity among persons known as subscribers.
Reduction
Lessening the possibility or severity of a loss.
Reinsurance
A form of insurance whereby one insurance company (the reinsurer) in consideration of a premium paid to it, agrees to indemnify another insurance company (the ceding company) for part or all of its liabilities from insurance policies it has issued.
Replacement Cost
The cost to replace damaged property with like kind and quality at current price, without any deduction for depreciation.
Representations
Statements made by the applicant on the insurance application that are believed to be true, but are not guaranteed to be true.
Retention
A method of dealing with risk by intentionally or unintentionally keeping a portion of it for the insured's account; the amount of responsibility assumed but not reinsured by the insurance company.
Retrospective Rating
A self-rating plan under which the actual losses during the policy period determine the final premium (subject to a minimum and maximum premium).
Right of Salvage
A provision in property insurance policy requiring that after payment of a total loss to insured property, the insured must transfer the title (or ownership) to the property to the insurer.
Risk
Uncertainty as to the outcome of an event when two or more possibilities exist.
Risk, Pure
The uncertainty or chance of a loss occurring in a situation that can only result in a loss or no change.
Risk, Speculative
The uncertainty or chance of a loss occurring in a situation that involves the opportunity for either loss or gain.
Robbery
The taking of property from another by using violence or the threat of violence.
Salvage
The amount of money realized from the sale of damaged merchandise or property. A salvage clause is found in ocean marine insurance and usually states that the rescuers of a ship are entitled to the salvage of the ship and cargo.
Settlement
The process by which an agreement is reached and a claim is resolved in liability insurance.
Severability of Interests
A provision that insurance applies separately to each insured in a policy, treating each individual as the only insured.
Sharing
A method of dealing with risk for a group of individual persons or businesses with the same or similar exposure to loss who share the losses that occur within that group.
Specific Insurance
A property insurance policy that covers a specific kind or unit of property for a specific amount of insurance.
Speculative Risk
The uncertainty or chance of a loss occurring in a situation that involves the opportunity for either loss or gain.
Split
Separately stated limits of liability for different coverages, which may be stated on a per person, per occurrence, per policy period basis, or can be divided between bodily injury and property damage.
Stated Amount
An amount of insurance scheduled in a property policy which is not subject to any coinsurance requirements in the event of a covered loss.
Statute Law
The written law as enacted by a legislative body (i.e., the laws of the state), which generally takes precedence in cases where both common law and statute law apply.
Stock Companies
Companies owned by the stockholders whose investments provide the capital necessary to establish and operate the insurance company.
Strict Liability
A liability that refers to damages caused by defective products even though the manufacturer's fault or negligence cannot be proven.
Subrogation
The acquisition by an insurer of an insured's rights against any third party for indemnification of loss or other payment, to the extent that the insurer pays the loss.
Superintendent (Commissioner, Director)
The head of the state department of insurance.
Surety Bond
A guarantee that debts and obligations will be carried out, and the benefits will be paid for losses caused by nonperformance.
Surplus Lines
Insurance that is not available in the regular marketplace from admitted insurers.
Theft
Any act of stealing or removing property from its rightful owner. Theft encompasses both burglary and robbery.
Third-Party Provisions
Insurance provisions that address the rights of someone other than the policyowner to have a secured financial interest in the insured property.
Tort
A wrongful act or the violation of someone's rights that leads to legal liability. Torts are classified as intentional or unintentional (referred to as negligence).
Transfer
A basic principle of insurance under which the risk of financial loss is assigned to another party.
Twisting
A form of misrepresentation in which an agent persuades an insured/owner to cancel, lapse, or switch policies, even when it's to the insured's disadvantage.
Umbrella Liability Policy
Coverage that provides extra protection against liability, and excess amount of insurance above the primary policy.
Unauthorized Insurer
An insurance company that has not applied, or has applied and been denied a Certificate of Authority.
Underinsured Motorist Coverage
Coverage in an automobile insurance policy under which the insurer will pay costs up to specified limits for bodily injury if the liable driver's policy limits are exhausted and the driver cannot pay the full amount for which they are liable.
Underwriter
A person who evaluates and classifies risks to accept or reject them on behalf of the insurer.
Underwriting
The process of reviewing, accepting or rejecting applications for insurance.
Unilateral Contract
A contract that legally binds only one party to contractual obligations after the premium is paid.
Uninsured Motorist Coverage
Coverage that allows the named insured, resident relative(s) and passengers in a covered auto to collect sums another driver would be legally liable to pay for bodily injury resulting from an auto accident, providing the accident was caused by an uninsured motorist, a hit-and-run driver or a driver whose insurance company is insolvent.
Unintentional Tort
The result of acting without proper care, generally referred to as negligence.
Unoccupied
A property that has contents or furnishings in it, but is not being used or lived in.
Utmost Good Faith
The fair and equal bargaining by both parties in forming the contract, where the applicant must make full disclosure of risk to the company, and the insurance company must be fair in underwriting the risk.
Vacant
A property that has no contents, furnishings, or occupants.
Valued Policy
A policy used when it is difficult to establish the actual cash value of insured property after a loss occurs because of its rarity or uniqueness. A valued policy provides for payment of the full policy amount in the event of a total loss without regard to actual value or depreciation.
Vicarious Liability
A type of liability in which one person is responsible for the acts of another. For example, employers may be vicariously liable for the actions of their employees, and parents may be held responsible for negligent acts of their children.
Waiting Period
Time between the beginning of a disability and the start of disability insurance benefits.
Waiver
The voluntary abandonment of a known or legal right or advantage.
Warranty
A material stipulation in the policy that if breached may void coverage.
Workers Compensation
Benefits required by state law to be paid to an employee by an employer in the case of injury, disability, or death as the result of an on-the-job hazard.
